<HEAD>Soviet Seaman Brought To Shore For Treatment After Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES seaman's condition; CORRECTS spelling of Soviet ship</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Coast Guard boat brought a Soviet
seaman ashore for medical aid after three of his fingers were
crushed while he was aboard a 270-foot Soviet fishing vessel.
   Anatoly Randin, 42, was listed in good condition Sunday in
Pacific Communities Hospital.
   Coast Guard Chief Chris Couch said a 44-foot motor lifeboat was
dispatched to the Soviet vessel, Polevd, at 8:35 p.m. Saturday
about 19 miles off Newport. Couch said he didn't know what caused
the injury.
   The Polevd is among a number of Soviet boats that have been
fishing off the coast, Couch said.
