<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     05-08 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No End In Sight For Screenwriters Walkout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soap opera actors say their characters have
started speaking ``See Dick run,'' Johnny Carson is actually tired
of time off and Bruce Willis has taken up gardening as a
scriptwriters strike enters week nine.
   Talks are suspended between the Writers Guild of America and the
Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers following the
WGA's walkout March 7 over residuals and creative control.
   And there's no relief in sight, with producer Stephen Cannell,
who's also a member of the guild, saying things could drag on until
January.
   ``The Writers Guild is a very militant union,'' Academy
Award-winning writer Dan Taradash said Friday. ``We believe in what
we believe.''
   Taradash, a former guild president and former president of the
Motion Picture Academy of Arts and Sciences, said the strike forced
him to stop work on a nearly completed script about Polish labor
leader Lech Walesa.
   A sequel to the movie ``Annie'' also reportedly has been
orphaned by the strike. ``Annie II,'' planned for a Christmas
release, couldn't get final touches made on its script.
   CBS, which had hoped for a comeback in the fall after an
unprecedented third-place finish this season, announced April 28
that it would push back the start of the new season from early
Septeber to late October at the earliest.
   Producers claim the strike has cost the industry more than $15
million in lost jobs and production time, with about 1,400 clerical
workers, cast and crew members laid off.
   The union struck when producers wanted to reformulate residual
payments for hour-long television shows sold into syndication.
Producers claim the shows are not selling well. Writers also want
an increase of residuals from foreign markets, and more control
over changes in their scripts.
   After nine weeks of reruns, Carson returns Wednesday, writing
his own monologue and otherwise ad-libbing his one-hour NBC show.
   Carson's contract allowing him generous time off has been the
subject of ``Tonight Show'' joking from time to time. But the
strike-forced vacation became no laughing matter, Carson said, with
longtime workers in his production company facing layoffs.
   Through a spokesman, Carson said that he was frustrated with
efforts to reach an independent contract with the guild that would
permit his scriptwriters to return.
   Talks with Carson and at least 80 other independent producers
are continuing. Scriptwriters voted April 14 not to grant
independent contracts until it had a number of them in hand to
avoid the divisiveness of only a few members returning to work.
   Arthur Sellers, a member of the guild negotiating committee,
said Friday that it was possible the membership ``may decide to
move ahead and sign independent contracts this month.''
   Meanwhile, the daytime soap operas have continued production.
   ``Scab scripts ain't fun,'' said actress Norma Connolly, who
plays Aunt Ruby on ``General Hospital.'' ``They make our days long
and hard. They're illiterate,'' she said Wednesday as she walked a
picket line with the guild.
   ``You have to continue,'' said Jerry Balme, one of the show's
producers. ``You owe it to the audience and to the network,'' he
said, adding: ``We miss (the writers). We want them back.''
   The writing is ``getting to look like `See Dick run,''' said
actress Peggy McCary of ``Days of Our Lives.''
   Labor-management relations can be unusual in Hollywood. Striking
scriptwriter Robert Goethals said he is surviving on tuna fish
sandwiches and loans from friends, who also happen to be producers.
   Producer Cannell, also a member of the Writers Guild, honors the
strike and stays away from his typewriter.
   ``Since I was a writer first, I'm not going to scab during the
strike,'' Cannell said. But he feels a conflict.
   ``I don't think it's going to settle on the Writers Guild terms
no matter what they think. I think it could go on to January if the
wrong set of philosophies get used ... if they keep saying the
companies are getting fat.''
   Like many other producers, Cannell has cut paychecks in half as
a means of keeping on staff. Cannell Productions turns out such
television series as ``Hunter,'' ``The A-Team,'' ``Hardcastle &
McCormick'' and ``The Rockford Files.''
   Meanwhile, ``Moonlighting'' star Bruce Willis has taken up
gardening. His ABC-TV series shut down early because of a lack of
scripts.
   Though he's not at work, Willis still has his problems.
   ``I'm having a lot of trouble with snails,'' Willis said
recently as he surveyed a tiny bed of marigolds and snapdragons.
</TEXT>
