<HEAD>Retired Argentine General Admits Ordering Publisher's Arrest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with police official declining
knowledge know about Suarez Mason's return. Pickup 3rd graf pvs
``In a...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede LOS ANGELES</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired Argentine general
arrested in the United States reportedly has been sent back to
Argentina Sunday to face murder charges but a police official here
could not confirm his arrival.
   Gen. Carlos Suarez Mason had acknowledged ordering the 1977
arrest of publisher Jacobo Timerman, The Los Angeles Times reported
Sunday.
   It said he made the statement Saturday before he was extradited
from San Francisco to face 39 murder charges in Argentina.
   Federal Police Chief Juan Angel Pirker, questioned by newsmen in
Buenos Aires about the report, said: ``Officially, I know nothing.''
   A Buenos Aires newspaper, Pagina 12, reported in its Sunday
edition that Suarez Mason had been ``expected to arrive this
morning'' at the capital's Ezeiza International Airport. But it
said strict security measures in San Francisco ``made it impossible
to verify whether Suarez Mason did depart or on what flight,
although it was certain that he left the (San Francisco) country
jail for the airport yesterday (Saturday) at 10:30 am. local time.''
   In a legal deposition, Suarez Mason discussed his role in
Argentina's military government during its ``dirty war'' against
suspected subversives in the 1970s, The Los Angelest Times reported.
   The ex-general was interviewed Friday and Saturday by Joanne
Hoeper, working on behalf of plaintiffs seeking damages in federal
court for victims of the Argentine junta. The junta has been blamed
for the deaths of thousands of people.
   Suarez Mason, 64, said he ordered Timerman's arrest after a
subordinate presented him with accusations that the publisher was
``friends with a man who owned a bank that funded guerrillas,'' the
Times quoted the attorney as saying.
   It was believed to be the first time Suarez Mason had
acknowledged his role in the arrest of Timerman, who described his
imprisonment and torture in the 1981 book ``Prisoner Without A
Name, Cell Without A Number.''
   The newspaper quoted Ms. Hoeper as saying Suarez Mason ``knew
Timerman was being interrogated. He said he listened to a
tape-recording of an interrogation...''
   The military confiscated Timerman's newspaper, La Opinion, which
campaigned against the junta's anti-Semitic policies. Timerman
spent 29 months in jail and under house arrest before being
expelled to Israel, where he became a citizen.
   Timerman returned to Buenos Aires last year and has received $5
million from the government as compensation for the loss of his
newspaper.
   Suarez Mason commanded the First Army Corps in Buenos Aires from
1976 to 1979. He fled the country after a civilian government took
over in 1983 and was arrested in January 1987 south of San
Francisco, where he was living under an assumed name.
   A panel of Argentina's civilian government has said at least
9,000 people disappeared during the nine-year rule by the military,
including 5,000 in the region where Suarez Mason was commander.
</TEXT>
