<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SupermarketSitters     05-08 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Supermarket Sitters,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grocery Store Provides Babysitting Service For Customers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARBONDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some kids call it the ``grocery-store
school'' and some parents call it a godsend. It's a baby-sitting
service at the supermarket that lets parents in peace, and leaves
more room in the cart for groceries.
   ``It's definitely helpful, especially when a mother has only two
hands and two children and (is) trying to grocery shop,'' said
35-year-old Karen Redfearn, who drives 17 miles from Herrin to shop
at the Country Fair store in Carbondale.
   ``It's terrific,'' she said.
   Located at the front of the Country Fair store, the baby-sitting
center has a color TV, a video cassette recorder, a 55-gallon
aquarium, two bulletin boards, five bean bags, five plastic trucks
and cars and stuffed animals.
   But if junior still gets bored, there's a 60-piece set of wooden
building blocks, a xylophone, an Etch-a-Sketch, a toy telephone and
a toy cash register. Safety scissors, glue and paint brushes,
crayons, markers and paper complete the picture.
   The 18-by-16-foot area is a separate room from the store. It has
brown carpeted floors and its walls are decorated with drawings by
the children.
   Big windows allow parents to check in on their youngsters while
they shop.
   ``My biggest problem is trying to get the kids to leave on
time,'' said Sandy Overstreet, 23, coordinator of the Carbondale
center. ``They like to go to grocery-store school _ some of the
kids call it that.''
   The child-care center opened in October and entertained its
6,000th youngster this past week.
   ``I've had a lot of positive comments from mothers, from
customers,'' said store manager Thomas J. Schmutz. ``I've had a lot
of older mothers tell me we should've done this 20 years ago.''
   ``The kids enjoy themselves more so than they enjoy grocery
shopping,'' said 32-year-old Connie Hirsh shortly after picking up
her year-old daughter at the center.
   A minimum $25 purchase at the store entitles parents to up to
two hours of free child care. After two hours, there's a $5-an-hour
charge.
   To ensure safety, the same person who checks a child in must
check him out, and parents must remain on the store premises while
the child is at the center.
   Children from age six months to six years are accepted.
   The idea came from Pete Bradham of Mount Vernon, owner of the
five Country Fairs in the Southern Illinois area. All but one offer
the baby-sitting service.
</TEXT>
