<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaunderingRing     05-08 0796</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Laundering Ring,0818</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0411 to fix byline</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Nice People' Who Bought Ranch Accused Of Money Laundering</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATOKA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The people who moved onto the George Ranch
late in 1985 made friends easily. Nobody in this rural area where a
man's background is his own business questioned their claim to have
bought the ranch with an inheritance.
   But the federal government alleges that the Atoka County ranch
north of Stringtown was a cover for laundering more than $1 million
in proceeds from international drug trafficking by claiming the
money came from cattle sales.
   Federal authorities also allege the isolated 2,889-acre
property, since renamed the Junior Ranch, was bought as a refuge
for Jose Contreras Subias, a Mexican national wanted for
questioning in the torture slaying of a U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration agent, the killings of nine Venezuelan national
guardsmen and the slaying of a Mexican federal police officer.
   Contreras was arrested April 1 in Salt Lake City and is jailed
in Los Angeles.
   Although federal officials now say they had been investigating
the southeast Oklahoma ranch for two years, the lid started coming
off when two Texans stumbled onto a nearby marijuana-growing
operation in August. They accused the owner of that ranch of
abduction and details started emerging at the subsequent trial.
   ``If he doesn't bother you, then why bother him? Just because
they came in with a lot of money?'' said Troy Gammon, Atoka County
clerk.
   When the Mexicans bought the ranch, it was viewed as a logical
investment of their money.
   ``They told us they inherited it. We believed them and we
welcomed them to the community,'' said Atoka City Manager Martha
Yates. ``We are still in shock.''
   Residents knew Contreras as Joe or Jose Guillen. People
interviewed last week said he was a model citizen who made friends
easily because of his gentel ways.
   ``They were planting feed, not dope,'' said a businessman who
would talk to a reporter only if his name were not used. ``They
came here to make it their home.''
   Contreras drove a hard bargain and wrote checks for purchases
rather than paying cash, the businessman said. Most big-ticket
items were financed.
   ``Does that sound like they were laundering money?'' he asked.
   But residents reported to be closely associated with Contreras
now deny knowing him well. People who attended parties at the ranch
threaten lawsuits if their names are mentioned in connection with
Contreras.
   Contreras, 42, originally was arrested in 1985 in Costa Rica
with Mexican drug king Rafael Caro Quintero. Quintero is awaiting
trial in the 1985 slaying of U.S. DEA agent Enrique Camarena.
   Contreras was sent to jail in Tijuana, Mexico, to stand trial
for the slaying of a Mexican federal agent. But he escaped in
October 1985 after bribing his jailers, according to documents
filed by DEA agents.
   Two months before his escape, a group of Mexicans negotiated to
buy the Atoka County ranch from rancher E.H. George, at a price of
$900,000, plus $99,000 for the cattle and hay, according to an FBI
affidavit.
   The $500,000 down payment originated as cashier's checks in
Tijuana on Oct. 22, 1985, six days before Contreras' escape. Ten
days after his escape, a checking account was opened at the Atoka
State Bank for Jose Guillen.
   From November 1985 through September 1987, more than $1.4
million was deposited in the Atoka State Bank account, according to
a federal affidavit. Neither the bank nor its officers has been
accused of wrongdoing. More money went into a bank in Durant.
   Contreras' alleged operation began to come unraveled in August,
when two Texans rode their three-wheelers onto the Bar-20 Ranch.
They said they were shot at, abducted and held in chains before
they escaped.
   Police raided the ranch and discovered more than 6,700 marijuana
plants. Ranch owner Elbert Lucien Johnson and two co-defendants
were convicted of running one of the state's largest marijuana
farms.
   At the trial, testimony brought up small details linking the two
ranches and the people associated with them. Among other things,
authorities allege Johnson provided the introductions for the
Mexicans to buy the George Ranch.
   ``We've been aware that they were there for a long time,'' U.S.
Attorney Roger Hilfiger said of the Junior Ranch. He said Johnson's
arrest ``let the cat out of the bag.''
   The day after Contreras' arrest, federal authorities raided the
Junior Ranch and another property near Plano, Texas, and seized
documents they are still studying. They also filed notice of
intention to seize the ranch and other property as the proceeds of
illegal drug transactions.
   No criminal charges have been filed related to the operation of
the Junior Ranch, but a federal grand jury convenes May 31 in
Muskogee.
</TEXT>
