<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0828 05-08 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0828,0531</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Sickman and Hogan deaths. An AM separate moved on
Sickman as a0849.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Costantino Nivola</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costantino Nivola, a sculptor whose
work ranged from huge bas-relief murals for public buildings to
female figurines on an intimate scale, died of a heart attack
Thursday at age 76.
   A native of Italy, he moved to New York in 1939 and became an
early champion of modern architecture.
   His commissions included a 110-foot-long mural for the Mutual
Insurance Co. of Hartford (Conn.) building; a war memorial in Falls
Church, Va.; a sand-sculptured wall for the former Olivetti Co.
showroom on New York's Fifth Avenue, now at Harvard, and numerous
sculptures and wall paintings for playgrounds in and around New
York.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Cruz Luna</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flamenco dancer Cruz Luna, who learned his
art in his native Spain and launched his career at age 17 with
appearances on television's Ed Sullivan and Dave Garroway shows,
died April 29. He was 50.
   Luna danced in an international tour with the Ballet Nacional of
Spain and in the Broadway show ``Ole! Ole!'' From 1960 to 1974, he
operated Cafe Madrid in North Beach and presented flamenco dancers
from around the world.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John H. Calhoun</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John H. Calhoun, an early civil rights leader and
a former city councilman, died Friday at age 88.
   Calhoun was a founder of the Atlanta Negro Voters League in 1948
and served as president of the Atlanta branch of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People in 1956-57.
   A Republican, he was elected to City Council in 1973, serving
until 1978.
