<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Elections, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0702,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Horse Racing Ballot Question Appears To Carry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with final Lubbock returns and additional Dallas
returns, Austin mayoral results; fixes style of pari-mutuel
throughout. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ballot proposal to authorize horse racing and
pari-mutuel betting was approved Saturday in Dallas County and, by
a narrow margin, in Lubbock County, where church leaders opposed it.
   They were the only two Texas counties voting on the issue
Saturday. Other counties voted in November, when residents
statewide approved a proposal to let counties determine whether to
allow wagering on horses.
   With 98 percent of the precincts reporting, the vote in Dallas
County was 40,793, or 56 percent, for pari-mutuel betting and
31,626, or 44 percent, against.
   The final tally in Lubbock County was 18,939, or 52 percent, for
pari-mutuel betting, and 17,541, or 48 percent, against.
   Throughout the state, voters were also electing mayors, city
councilmen and school trustees.
   The voting stirred limited interest in Dallas County, where
elections administrator Bruce Sherbet said he expected only about
10 percent of the registered voters to turn out.
   But Lubbock City Secretary Ranette Boyd said her telephone was
kept busy with calls from people wanting to know where they could
vote. She predicted a Lubbock County turnout almost twice that of
the last general election.
   Pari-mutuel betting was the most volatile issue on the ballot in
the county since a narrow vote almost 20 years ago to legalize
mixed-drink sales.
   Proponents of horse race betting tout it as a
multimillion-dollar economic boon; opponents say it will lead to
crime and compulsive gambling.
   Citizens Against Pari-Mutuel Gambling campaigned against the
proposition largely through a mailing to 100 local churches, said
Gene Glaeser, minister of Broadway Church of Christ in Lubbock.
   In the Austin mayoral race, incumbent Mayor Frank Cooksey came
in second to former City Councilman Lee Cooke, but six other
candidates split enough votes to force a runoff.
</TEXT>
