<HEAD>Hostage Wife Appeals to Reagan to Act for His Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of American hostage Terry
Anderson has issued an appeal to President Reagan to help free him
from captors in Lebanon.
   Madeleine Bassil made a televised statement Saturday to Reagan,
saying, ``Mr. President, you probably have never heard of me but
you certainly know that Terry Anderson, hostage in Lebanon for over
three years, has a family.''
   Ms. Bassil, who is Lebanese, said their 2-year-old daughter
Sulome ``cannot accept my excuses any longer of why her daddy is
only a picture.''
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for the Associated
Press, was kidnapped in Beirut March 16, 1985. He has never seen
his daughter.
   Ms. Bassil's plea to Reagan comes four days after three French
hostages were released in Beirut by the Islamic Jihad, the same
pro-Iranian group that claims to hold Anderson.
   ``Compromising now is the only solution,'' she told Reagan.
``Are we to wait (for) an election before we see our loved one? We
can't wait any longer, Mr. President. You must do something now
before things get out of hand.''
   Another American hostage, Thomas Sutherland, dean of agriculture
at the American University of Beirut, is also believed held by
Islamic Jihad. He was kidnapped in June 1985.
   Anderson and Sutherland are among 18 foreign hostages, including
nine Americans, being held hostage.
