<1ST_LINE>r i BC-India-Sikhs     05-08 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-India-Sikhs,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>23 Die, 25 Wounded In Sikh Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh gunmen fired into a group of
migrant workers at a wedding celebration in Haryana state Saturday
night, killing 13 people and wounding at least 25 others, police
said.
   Sikh extremists were blamed for 10 other deaths late Saturday
and early Sunday in the neighboring northern Indian state of
Punjab, including a Hindu family of four and its two servants, the
United News of India reported.
   The extremists have been waging a guerrilla campaign since 1982
for more political autonomy or an independent homeland for Sikhs in
Punjab. The latest killings raised to more than 940 the number of
deaths blamed on the Sikh separatists since the start of the year.
   Most of the victims have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs in Punjab
who oppose the radicals' guerrilla campaign.
   The migrant workers were killed near Panipat, 90 miles south of
the joint Punjab-Haryana state capital at Chandigarh.
   Police said that six gunmen crossed from Punjab state into
Haryana and fired AK-47 automatic rifles at the workers as they
were celebrating a wedding.
   Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus.
   Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of India's 800 million
population but are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
