<HEAD>Court Delays Expulsion of Arab-American</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Sunday delayed the
deportation of Mubarak Awad, an Arab-American, and ordered the
government to explain its decision, a court spokesman said.
   Justice Shoshana Netanyahu scheduled a hearing on Awad's appeal
for Monday morning, spokesman Shmaryahu Cohen told The Associated
Press.
   Awad, 44, an advocate of civil disobedience, was detained
Thursday. The expulsion order was issued Friday and was to take
effect at midnight Sunday.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir issued the expulsion order against
Awad, alleging he incited violence during the 5-month-old
Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
According to U.N. figures, 184 Palestinians and two Israelis have
been killed since the violence began Dec. 8.
   Israel has also accused Awad of being behind a leaflet issued
last month that urged Palestinians to throw firebombs and rocks at
Israeli targets.
   Israel radio said Awad filed an appeal against the deportation
Sunday after his attorneys visited him in a Jerusalem jail, where
he has been on hunger strike since his arrest.
   The Jerusalem-born Awad heads the Center for Non-Violent Studies
in Jerusalem. Some of the methods preached by Awad, such as
boycotts of Israeli goods, nonpayment of taxes and sit-ins, have
been adopted by underground leaders of the uprising.
   Awad has said that unlike Palestine Liberation Organization
extremists, he advocates peaceful coexistence between Israelis and
Palestinians.
   Awad is a U.S. citizen who has a home in Wapakoneta, Ohio. The
deportation order prompted protests from the U.S. government, which
urged Israel to reconsider the move.
