<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-88 1207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Psychiatrist-Fortune Bjt   05-08 1080</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Psychiatrist-Fortune, Bjt,1113</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prominent Psychiatrist Accused Of Unethical Conduct In Fortune
Squabble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the American Psychiatric
Association is accused in a probate dispute of exploiting a woman
who gave him $80,000 a year in trusts and willed $5 million to a
psychiatric institute she founded during a decade of psychoanalysis
with him.
   The legal battle is between Dr. George Pollock, one of Chicago's
leading psychoanalysts, and Francis L. Lederer II, only child of
Anne P. Lederer, who died in 1984 at age 78.
   Pollock denies any wrongdoing.
   Mrs. Lederer left most of her estimated $5 million estate to a
non-profit institute she established four years earlier to promote
psychiatric research and music. None of the money has been paid,
however, because her son is contesting her will in Cook County
Probate Court. A trial is scheduled to begin July 5.
   Lederer accused Pollock of improperly using his influence while
treating his mother for depression to urge her to create the
institute and ``wrongfully inducing'' her to bequeath her fortune
to it, according to court documents.
   Pollock, who was attending the annual meeting of the association
in Montreal, referred calls for comment to his attorney, Robert
Tepper of Chicago. Tepper said he had advised Pollock not to
discuss the case.
   But Pollock denied the allegations in an affidavit Dec. 4, 1986.
   ``I never made false representations to her for the purpose and
with the intent of improperly controlling, dominating and
misleading her and unduly influencing and wrongfully inducing her
to execute her last will,'' Pollock said.
   Tepper said he saw ``no support or substantiation'' for claims
that Mrs. Lederer was incompetent or unduly influenced.
   ``But anyone can file a lawsuit, and these days it has become a
recognized means of social expression,'' he added.
   Dr. Larry Strasburger, a Harvard Medical School psychiatrist who
reviewed Pollock's conduct in Mrs. Lederer's case at the request of
her son's attorneys, contended in a deposition that there were
grounds for a malpractice suit. He was paid $200 an hour as an
expert witness.
   Strasburger said he reviewed Mrs. Lederer's prescription records
and found she was taking enough medication to become
psychologically and physically addicted.
   Pollock, who will step down as president when the association's
annual meeting ends Thursday, also is director of the Chicago
Institute for Psychoanalysis and a Northwestern University Medical
School professor.
   Pollock conducted up to five sessions a week with Mrs. Lederer
from 1969 to 1980, when he transferred her case to two other
psychiatrists, saying he needed more time for other professional
duties, court documents show.
   Pollock continued prescribing medication for her until 1983, and
records show he told the succeeding psychiatrists in a letter:
   ``Incidentally, I do hope that you are charging her a full fee
for your housecalls and visits. She can well afford it.''
   During the years Mrs. Lederer was a patient of Pollock:
   _She established a trust fund that has paid Pollock $50,000 a
year since 1976 and will continue paying him through 1993. She
established a second trust that has paid Pollock's family $30,000 a
year since 1978. Court records aren't clear when the second trust
expires.
   _From 1969 until her death, Mrs. Lederer donated $601,330 to the
Chicago Institute for Psychoanalysis. Of that money, $60,233 went
to a depression research fund controlled by Pollock.
   _In 1980, she created the Anne P. Lederer Research Institute.
Pollock worked for a short time as a paid consultant to the
institute, but said in his affidavit that ``there is no secret
agreement'' for him to participate in its future operations. He
also denied receiving any benefit from Mrs. Lederer's will.
   _Mrs. Lederer dismissed her longtime attorneys when they
expressed reservations about her institute and hired Chicago lawyer
Leonard Schanfield, a friend of Pollock.
   _In 1982, she amended her will to leave $200,000 to her son,
several thousand dollars to two grandchildren and the rest of her
money _ estimated at $5 million _ to the Lederer Research
Institute. She also named Pollock, Schanfield and Continental
Illinois National Bank & Trust Co. as co-executors of her estate.
   Tepper said Mrs. Lederer's son was worth about $2 million before
her death and that when she died he inherited about $6 million from
a trust established by her father, E.J. Pollock, vice president and
comptroller of Sears Roebuck & Co. in the 1930s. The two Pollock
families are not related.
   Mrs. Lederer referred to her son's wealth to explain in her last
will why she was leaving most of her money ``to my foundation.''
   Schanfield said Mrs. Lederer told him that he was one of four
lawyers referred to her by Pollock to review her estate planning
and help her establish the research institute.
   ``Dr. Pollock played no role whatsoever in establishing that
institute,'' Schanfield said Friday in a telephone interview.
``Mrs. Lederer set it up.''
   In their briefs, attorneys for Mrs. Lederer's son, Kevin
Murnighan and Phil Doran, suggest she was dependent on Pollock.
   The attorneys contended that after Mrs. Lederer's husband, a
doctor, died in 1973, ``Dr. Pollock took the place of her husband
and he constantly advised her on all facets of life, from where she
was going to live, to what she was going to eat, to what medical
treatment to get, to what raises to give the housekeeper.''
   Tepper said Mrs. Lederer and Pollock were friends, and that the
psychiatrist accepted her financial gifts ``because there was no
reason not to accept'' them, a point of ethical debate.
   But Strasburger wrote: ``His acceptance of large gifts to his
family, his institution and himself occurred in a pattern of
conduct evidencing gross disregard for psychoanalytic principle and
psychiatric propriety.''
   Dr. Robert Weinstock, a psychiatrist and associate professor at
the University of California at Los Angeles Medical School, said he
knew of no specific guidelines on ethics that prohibit
psychiatrists from accepting gifts or donations from patients.
   ``I can say that it would be unusual while somebody is in
treatment to accept large gifts,'' he said in a telephone
interview. ``It's not standard to do that.''
   The American Psychiatric Association's principles of medical
ethics do not contain a specific provision against accepting money
or other gifts from patients beyond professional fees.
   But the principles do say a psychiatrist ``should not use the
unique position of power afforded him by the psychotherapeutic
situation to influence the patient in any way not directly relevant
to the treatment goals.''
</TEXT>
