<DOCNO> AP880508-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-88 1208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TonyNominations     05-08 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tony Nominations,0808</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Field Crowded In Many Categories As Tony Award Nominations To Be
Announced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tony Awards nominating committee has a happy
problem this year, more talent and worthy performances in some
categories than can be squeezed into the customary four nominations.
   Contrary to what has happened in some recent seasons, this year
there should be some interesting contests in Broadway's equivalent
of Hollywood's Oscars.
   The nominations are due to be announced Monday. The winners of
the 42nd annual awards, to be chosen by a vote by more than 600
theater professionals, will be announced June 5 in a program
broadcast nationally on CBS.
   Three plays eligible for ``best play'' Tony contention are by
playwrights who have previously won the Pulitzer Prize, David
Mamet, August Wilson and Lanford Wilson.
   The last play to open before the Tony deadline was Mamet's
``Speed the Plow,'' which got lavish media attention because it
stars rock star-actress Madonna. Mamet's ``Glengarry Glen Ross''
won a Pulitzer in 1984.
   ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone,'' set early this century, is
August Wilson's latest in his series of plays about the black
experience in America, each set in a different decade. His
``Fences,'' set in the 1950s, which won him a Pulitzer Prize last
year, is still running.
   Lanford Wilson, who won the 1980 Pulitzer Prize for ``Talley's
Folly,'' one of his cycle of plays about the Talley family on
Broadway, has a contender this season that isn't in that series,
``Burn This.''
   Three possible ``best play'' nominees are based on real
happenings. ``M. Butterfly'' is about a French diplomat who had an
affair with a Chinese Communist thinking the man is a woman. ``A
Walk in the Woods'' shows an American and a Russian arms negotiator
talking informally outside their conference room in Geneva. And
``Breaking the Code,'' which opened early in the season and is no
longer running, is about Alan Turing, who broke the German's code
in World War II.
   In musicals, Andrew Lloyd Webber's ``The Phantom of the Opera''
is by far the season's hottest ticket and is almost assured a Tony
nomination. It's not necessarily assured the Tony, since the
Broadway community's Tony voters are proud of putting their
artistic opinions ahead of box-office sales.
   Anything Stephen Sondheim composes also is almost assured a Tony
nomination. He won the Pulitzer Prize for drama in 1985 for
``Sunday in the Park with George.'' His ``Into the Woods,'' fairy
tales with ``realistic'' endings, opened this season.
   There's also ``Chess,'' another American-Russian confrontation,
with music by the two writers for the rock group ABBA and lyrics by
Lloyd Webber's old partner, Tim Rice; ``Sarafina!'', a South
African musical set in a terrorized schoolyard; and ``The Gospel at
Colonus,'' the Oedipus story told in gospel music. Three which
didn't run long are ``Roza,'' ``Mail'' and ``Teddy and Alice.''
   The nominating committee's trouble with the best-actor category
this year should be narrowing nominees down to four. Derek Jacobi
was virtually a one-man show in ``Breaking the Code.'' John
Malkovich, no longer in the cast, was a bravura wild man in ``Burn
This.'' Robert Prosky plays the Russian negotiator, the meatier of
the two parts, in ``A Walk in the Woods.'' John Lithgow is the
French diplomat in ``M. Butterfly.''
   Christopher Plummer has the title role in ``Macbeth.'' Joe
Mantegna and Ron Silver costar in ``Speed the Plow.'' Frank
Langella had the showy title role in ``Sherlock's Last Case,''
which opened last August and ran into December.
   As usual, starring parts for women are fewer. Blythe Danner, who
now has left the cast, was Blanche in ``A Streetcar Named Desire.''
Joan Allen played opposite Malkovich in ``Burn This.'' Prosky and
Lithgow act opposite men in their plays. Glenda Jackson is Lady
Macbeth. Madonna is the third character in ``Speed the Plow.''
   For performers in musicals, Michael Crawford and Sarah Brightman
sing the phantom and his obsession in ``The Phantom of the Opera.''
Patti LuPone and Howard McGillin sing Cole Porter in the revival of
``Anything Goes.'' Joel Grey stars again in the revived ``Cabaret.''
   Len Cariou sang Teddy Roosevelt in the departed ``Teddy and
Alice.'' Bernadette Peters opened but no longer plays in ``Into the
Woods.'' Judy Kuhn forms the triangle on the chessboard of David
Carroll and Philip Casnoff in ``Chess.''
   Longer shots for nominations are Michael Rupert, starring in
``Mail,'' which he composed, and Georgia Brown singing Gilbert
Becaud songs in ``Roza,'' which was based on the movie ``Madame
Rosa,'' starring Simone Signoret.
   The Tonies are named for actress Antoinette Perry, who was
active in the American Theater Wing during the 1940s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
