<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Soviet-Nuclear,0119</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Hold Nuclear Test on Arctic Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union conducted an underground nuclear
test Sunday on an Arctic island to upgrade its military technology,
Tass said.
   The blast at Novaya Zemlya island north of the Arctic Circle
measured from 20 to 150 kilotons, the official news agency said.
Twenty kilotons, the equivalent of 20,000 tons of TNT, was the
force of the U.S. atomic bomb dropped on Hiroshima, Japan, in 1945.
   The last Soviet nuclear test was on May 4 at the Semipalatinsk
range in Soviet Kazakhstan.
   Soviet officials have proposed a ban on nuclear tests, but the
United States disagrees with the Soviets on how to enforce it.
</TEXT>
