<HEAD>Authorities Force-Feed Jailed Taiwan Dissident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities resumed force-feeding a jailed
dissident after his hunger strike put him near death, human rights
officials said Sunday.
   Shih Ming-teh, 47, was convicted of instigating a 1979
anti-government riot in Kaohsiung. He went on a hunger strike in
March 1986, saying the government had failed to release other
political prisoners involved in the riot.
   He was forcibly fed a high-protein liquid since he began his
hunger stirke. But the feeding stopped April 22 after he threatened
suicide.
   The Taiwan Association for Human Rights said that since
Saturday, Shih had been fed again with glucose through a nasal tube
at a military-run hospital.
   The group quoted hospital doctor Fu Yih-chu as saying Shih's
health had deteriorated with unstable breathing, low blood sugar,
high blood pressure and a malfuctioning liver.
