<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Plot     05-08 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Plot,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turk Acquitted of Firing at Pope Reported Detained in France</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Turk who was acquitted of conspiracy
in the shooting of Pope John Paul II has been detained in France,
it was reported Sunday.
   The Istanbul daily Hurriyet quoted Sabahattin Cakmakoglu,
general director of the Security Department of the Interior
Ministry, as saying French authorities notified them Friday of the
detention of Oral Celik.
   Cakmakoglu told Hurriyet he did not have any other details.
   Other Turkish dailies quoted unidentified Interior Minister
officials as saying they too were notified Friday night about
Celik's detention.
   Celik is wanted in Turkey on charges of complicity in the 1979
murder of Abdi Ipekci, a liberal newspaper editor in Istanbul, and
of murder in the killing of a teacher, Nevzat Yildirim, three
months later in Malatya.
   Cakmakoglu said Turkey had reiterated to France its request for
Celik's extradition.
   In March 1986, a court in Rome found Celik, three Bulgarians and
two Turks innocent of charges of conspiring to kill the pope on May
13, 1981 in St. Peter's Square.
   Another Turk, Mehmet Ali Agca, was convicted of trying to kill
John Paul and was sentenced to life in prison. Celik had been
described as Agca's right arm and best friend.
   The prosecutor had asked for a life sentence for Celik, who was
at large and tried in absentia on charges of firing at the pope
with Agca. Celik was acquitted for lack of evidence.
   Under Italian law, acquittal for lack of evidence does not
amount to a complete finding of innocence. It means that the court
believes there is a possibility of guilt but that it did not hear
enough evidence to support a conviction.
   Turkish officials were not immediately available to comment on
the reports of his detention. In Paris, the Foreign Ministry said
it had no comment on the reports.
</TEXT>
