<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Denmark-ElectionGlance     05-08 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denmark-Election Glance,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danish Election at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Denmark-Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are facts and figures on
Denmark's general election called for Tuesday in a dispute over its
nuclear arms policy in light of its membership in NATO:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ELIGIBLE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   There are 3.9 million Danes over 18 who are eligible to vote,
out of the country's population of 5.1 million.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AT STAKE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   All seats in the 179-member unicameral legislature, the
Folketing, which sits for a maximum four-year term. A party must
get at least 2 percent of the vote to win a seat. Greenland and the
Faroe Islands are represented by two deputies each.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RUNNING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   There are 12 parties contesting the vote.
   _ The center-right governing coalition, now holding 70 seats, is
comprised of the Conservative, Liberal, Center Democratic and
Chrstian People's parties.
   _ The opposition bloc controls 81 seats and includes the Social
Democratic and the Socialist People's parties.
   _ The non-aligned parties are the nine-seat Progress Party, an
anti-tax group on the far right; the 11-seat Social-Liberals, which
supports the government on domestic issues and votes with the
opposition on foreign issues; and the maverick far-left Common
Course Party with 4 seats. The four members from Greenland and the
Faroes split evenly between the oppostion and coalition.
   _ Also running are the environmentalist Danish Green Party, the
Communist Party, and the Leftwing Socialists.
   The leading candidates are Prime Minister Poul Schlueter, 59, of
the Conservative Party, who has headed the government since 1982;
Svend Auken, 45, named Social Democratic leader after the previous
election; and Niels Helveg Petersen, 49, of the Social-Liberals,
who could form a government in the event of an election stalemate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE ISSUE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A resolution sponsored by the Social Democrats obliging Denmark
to notify visiting warships that nuclear arms are barred from
Danish ports in peacetime. The April 14 resolution, which passed
75-58, was sharply criticized by NATO as a challenge to its common
nuclear strategy, and Schlueter called the election rather than
carry out the motion.
   Schlueter portrayed the vote as a choice between preserving or
risking Denmark's full membership in NATO. Auken said the
government is exaggerating the defense issue, and wants to broaden
the campaign to economic issues such as unemployment and welfare
spending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
