<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Singapore     05-08 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singapore,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singapore Defends Ouster Of U.S. Diplomat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Sunday defended its ouster of a
U.S. diplomat and offered to back up charges that he meddled in
local politics.
   Washington agreed with ``deep regret'' to a request from
Singapore Saturday to withdraw E. Mason (Hank) Hendrickson, a
political attache.
   The government also asked that Hendrickson be reprimanded along
with two unidentified senior State Department officials who it said
sanctioned his activities.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Richard Gong denied allegations, made by
the Home Affairs Ministry, that Hendrickson interfered in
Singapore's politics.
   In meeting members of the political opposition, ``which appears
to be the basis of the Singapore government's protest, Mr.
Hendrickson was doing what American diplomats are expected to do in
any country, namely to keep in touch with a broad spectrum of
individuals in order to report accurately developments in the
country in question,'' Gong said.
   In a statement Sunday, Singapore said it would not
``capriciously or arbitrarily expel diplomats from Singapore,
especially when the diplomat in question represents a friendly
nation.''
   ``The assertion that Hendrickson has not in any way acted
improperly can only be a diplomatic fig leaf which the government
is content to allow the United States to wear,'' the statement said.
   Singapore contends that Hendrickson met with opposition
activists and urged them to contest upcoming elections.
   Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew's People's Action Party is heavily
favored to retain control of this island republic of 2.6 million
people in elections that must be held by December 1989.
   The party holds all but one of the 79 seats in parliament and
there is no viable opposition capable of dislodging it.
   Hendrickson ``was trying to manipulate and instigate
Singaporeans, in order to bring about a particular political
outcome,'' the government said.
   His explusion was an unprecedented jolt to normally warm
relations between the two countries. Lee long ago established close
personal and political ties with Washington, and recently returned
from ``private'' talks with President Reagan and Secretary of State
George Shultz.
   The United States is the largest buyer of Singapore's exports
and one of the biggest investors in this former British colony that
gained full independence in 1965.
   The diplomatic tiff is the latest in a chain of events that
began with the arrests last year of 22 Singaporeans accused of
belonging to a ``clandestine communist network.'' They were seized
under the Internal Security Act which allows for indefinate
detention without trial.
   All but one were freed by Dec. 26, most of them with
restrictions on their movements.
   Among them was a lawyer, Patrick Seong, who allegedly was urged
by Hendrickson to fight the government.
   Seong was arrested again on April 19 along with eight of the 22
former detainees. That was less than 24 hours after the eight
proclaimed their innocence and said they had been abused and
coerced into making incriminating statements late last year.
   On April 28, the Home Affairs Ministry said the eight had sworn
fresh declarations withdrawing their allegations and reconfirming
their original guilt. They are still behind bars and officials said
an investigation continues.
   Besides Seong, 34, Hendrickson was linked by the government to
lawyer Patrick Seow, 59. Seow was arrested Friday, hours after he
appeared in court seeking the release of two of those arrested
April 19.
   Seow, a former solictor-general and one time president of the
Law Society, is being held without charge under the Internal
Security Act ``for purposes of investigation into foreign
interferences in Singapore's internal affairs.''
   Trade and Industry Minister Lee Hsien Loong said two distinct
phases of the so-called political movement had become clear. One
was a Marxist conspiracy involving the original 22, the other was
separate action by foreign elements who made use of the detainees
to meddle in domestic politics, he said.
</TEXT>
