<DOCNO> AP880508-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     05-08 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marchers Demand Marcos' Return; Aquino Stands Firm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of supporters of former
President Ferdinand E. Marcos marched through the capital Sunday
and demanded that the ousted leader be allowed to return from exile
to attend his mother's funeral.
   President Corazon Aquino, in a radio broadcast hours after the
march, reiterated that Marcos could not return because his presence
might cause trouble and destabilize the government.
   ``I know that some people were upset that he was not allowed to
return,'' Mrs. Aquino said in her weekly radio program, ``Ask the
President.''
   ``But I think the great majority are concerned that, first of
all, we preserve whatever gains we have attained during the past
two years,'' she said. ``And it is very necessary to preserve the
stability that we have attained for the good of the entire
country.''
   Mrs. Aquino indicated she might allow a visit by any of Marcos'
three children, but she said the family must make a formal request
to give the government time to prepare for security.
   The president said no requests had been made.
   Officials have said the ban on Marcos, who lives in Hawaii,
applied to all members of his immediate family. Immigration
officials said they would be arrested if they entered the
Philippines.
   There have been news reports that Marcos' son, Ferdinand Jr.,
planned to sneak into the country to represent his father at the
funeral, which hasn't been scheduled. The former president's other
relatives denied the reports.
   About 4,000 marchers blew whistles, shot off firecrackers and
chanted, ``Marcos! Marcos!'' along a six-mile route from a downtown
park to a suburban Roman Catholic church where the body of Josefa
Edralin-Marcos lay in state.
   Mrs. Edralin-Marcos died in a hospital Wednesday at the age of
95. Just before she died, Marcos' mother sent Mrs. Aquino a
deathbed wish that her son be allowed to return so she could see
him one last time.
   Marcos fled to Hawaii with his wife and three children during
the February 1986 ``People Power Revolution'' that ended his
20-year rule and swept Mrs. Aquino to the presidency.
   He said in a statement Wednesday that he will ``exhaust all
possibilities'' to attend the funeral. Marcos' younger brother,
Pacifico, and sister, Fortuna Marcos-Barba, said they have not set
a burial date because they hope Mrs. Aquino will change her mind.
   At the head of the march was an empty, makeshift coffin draped
with a Philippine flag and a sign saying, ``Ninoy has died, Cory
has risen, Marcos will come again.''
   Ninoy was the nickname of Mrs. Aquino's husband, former Sen.
Benigno Aquino Jr., who was assassinated Aug. 21, 1983 as he
stepped off a plane after returning to the Philippines from three
years' voluntary exile in the United States. The assassination
triggered waves of protest that contributed to Marcos' downfall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
