<DOCNO> AP880508-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TornadoDeaths     05-08 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tornado Deaths,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Warning For Tornado That Killed Two</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRETNA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusual late-night tornado slammed into a
mobile home without warning, killing a woman and her baby and
critically injuring her husband while thunderstorms caused
scattered damage in eastern Nebraska.
   Two-inch hailstones broke windows in Omaha and wind up to 60 mph
pushed over trees and damaged other mobile homes.
   The tornado touched down with no warning, ripping the roof off a
farmhouse and causing extensive damage to another house as well as
the mobile home shortly before 11 p.m. Saturday, said Sarpy County
Chief Deputy Lee Polikov.
   ``The weather service is not feeling too good about not being
able to get a warning out before,'' Polikov said Sunday. ``It is
unusual to have them that late at night in this area. They usually
are in the evening. It couldn't be seen by radar.''
   Steve Byrd, a meteorologist for the National Weather Service in
Omaha, said Sunday that the tornado touched down only for a few
minutes. He confirmed the funnel was not detected by radar.
   ``It was the same thunderstorm that we followed with 1-inch hail
in the Lincoln area, but as far as showing a tornado, that wasn't
apparent through our radar detector,'' he said. ``We started
detecting it in western Douglas County, but that was after it had
touched down. It apparently touched down and then went right back
up.''
   Small tornadoes that touch down only briefly are much more
difficult to detect than large ones, Byrd said.
   Two-year-old Lynn True was dead at the scene, Polikov said. Her
mother, Joan True, 29, died of head injuries early Sunday at
University of Nebraska Medical Center in Omaha, said hospital
spokesman Tom O'Connor.
   Dennis True, 31, underwent surgery and was reported in critical
but stable condition at Midlands Hospital in Papillion.
   In Omaha, more than 10 miles to the northeast, minor injuries
were reported, trees were knocked down and dozens of small power
outages were reported, along with hail as large as 2 inches in
diameter.
   Byrd said the hail broke windows at his office in north Omaha.
   ``We've got hailstones out here that are as big as hen's eggs.
They are bigger than golf balls,'' he said.
   Six to eight mobile homes in Omaha were damaged, including one
that flipped on its side, said Larry Hamilton Sr., assistant chief
of the Millard Volunteer Fire Department.
   Wahoo, Fremont, Blair and Columbus were hit by wind as strong as
60 mph, the weather service said.
</TEXT>
