<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Army-Bolts     05-08 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Army-Bolts,490</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dingell: Weak Bolts Causing `Serious Problems' in Two Army Units</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army has ``serious problems'' in two of
its front-line units because of continuing problems with weak bolts
in some vehicles, Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., said Sunday.
   The problem may be even more extensive than that because the two
units received their bolts from the same depots that supply other
Army units, both here and overseas, said Dingell, chairman of the
House Energy and Commerce Committee.
   Dingell also heads the investigations subcommittee, which held
widely publicized hearings last August revealing problems of bolts
and fasteners that weren't as strong as expected.
   The result is that wheel assemblies on some Army vehicles, such
as trucks and the all-purpose ``Hum-V,'' may come lose, according
to testimony that will be presented Monday to the investigations
subcommittee during a follow-up hearing.
   A subcommittee staff report said the problem fasteners were
still found in large numbers in vehicles of the 7th Infantry
division at Fort Ord, Calif., and the 9th Regiment at Fort Carson,
Colo.
   Tansill Johnson, a spokeswoman for the Army Material Command,
which oversees the depots that supply the bolts, admitted the
service is still having problems.
   ``We're very concerned about this,'' Ms. Johnson said. ``We have
been remiss in not educating soldiers at the lowest level about
using the right grade of bolts.''
   But she noted that in a series of tests, ``we've found that many
of the bolts are still effective, even though they are substandard
compared to contract specifications.''
   The subcommittee staff report noted that ``the vehicles of the
units we visited contained a number of fasteners from foreign
manufacturers whose bolts had previously been found substandard in
numerous laboratory tests.''
   ``The combat units were experiencing severe fastener problems on
their vehicles to the extent that the combat readiness of some
units was affected,'' it said.
   Because the fasteners were not as strong as they should have
been, some of them came lose in front wheel assemblies of the
Hum-V, the investigators found. ``This caused tire wear, fastener
failure, and if not corrected, loss of steering.''
   In a check of the 9th Regiment, half of the 102 Hum-Vs checked
had loose fasteners and seven had been lost from service because
the problem was so severe, the subcommittee investigators found.
   One officer got so frustrated with trying to get the right
fasteners that he ``bought replacement bolts from the civilian
economy with money from his own pocket in order to get the unit's
vehicles ready. By a stroke of luck, he obtained domestic bolts at
the local hardware store,'' the report said.
   Part of the problem is that bolts are stored in a variety of
bins and the containers aren't always clearly marked, according to
Ms. Johnson.
   The subcommittee investigators agreed, reporting that Army
maintenance personnel ``admitted that over 50 percent of their bins
contained fasteners of unknown quality and complained that they
were not receiving sufficient information to purge the suspect
fasteners.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
