<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-88 1450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IowaRiots     05-08 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iowa Riots,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wild ISU Weekend Prompts Festival Reappraisal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After sparking three consecutive nights of
violence, Iowa State University's annual spring festival faces an
overhaul in order to curb excessive drinking, school officials and
student organizers of the festival agree.
   ``We're looking to work with the university and city to see what
changes we can make,'' said Curt Ford, a sophomore from Geneseo,
Ill., who is on the committee for the Veishea festival, an annual
long weekend of student activities.
   Early Sunday, eight law officers were injured and 45 people were
arrested as student celebrations coinciding with Veishea concluded.
There were two arrests early Friday and nine early Saturday.
   ``This certainly mars what has been a very good weekend for
Veishea. But we're going to have to reassess the whole Veishea
activity ... and the amount of time students have off,'' said
Thomas Thielen, university vice president of student affairs.
   He was on the scene early Sunday as raucous students set fires
in streets and pelted officers and police vehicles with rocks and
bottles.
   Student organizers of the 66th annual Veishea festival disavowed
the rioting, saying it was not connected with any formal activities
that included a parade on Saturday that was followed by the
football team's spring game. occurred. The event was named by
taking the first letter in the name of each of Iowa State's
original colleges.
   ``We've been trying to promote the non-alcoholic aspect of
Veishea this year,'' Ford said later Sunday. ``We don't know why
things got out of hand.'' Helmeted police clashed with an estimated
crowd of 2,000 early Sunday in the heart of campus, where bonfires
were fed by sofas and other furniture carried by beer-drinking
revelers.
   Nightly disturbances at the annual spring festival started
Thursday and grew progressively worse before the festival ended
Sunday. Like the previous two nights, the latest disturbance
appeared to start with private parties.
   ``It was pretty ugly for a while,'' said Ames Police Chief
Dennis Ballantine. ``Frankly, I haven't seen anything like this
since the early 1970s and the Vietnam war protests.
   ``The only difference is those people had a legitimate gripe.
These people didn't. They were just drunk.''
   As state, county and city law enforcement officers helped
firefighters move in to put out the fires Sunday, they were pelted
with bottles and rocks thrown by crowd members. Two police cars
were damaged when hit by concrete blocks.
   At least two people in the crowd were burned, but not seriously,
said police dispatcher Pam Roberts.
   When law officers had little success persuading the crowd to
disperse, the school's popular basketball coach, Johnny Orr, came
to campus after 3 a.m. and pleaded with students to go home. Orr
warned them their actions were damaging the school's reputation.
   The crowd broke up a short time later.
   Most of the 45 people arrested were charged with inciting to
riot, an aggravated misdemeanor.
   Eight officers were treated and released at Mary Greeley
Hospital, with two requiring stitches to close wounds.
   The violence erupted as dozens of officers from the Ames police
department, the Story County sheriff's department, the state patrol
and campus security lined both sides of Welch Avenue, a strip of
taverns and small shops, escorting firefighters to the bonfires.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880508-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-88 1452EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MoslemSchism 1stLd-Writethru a0738 05-08 0986</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moslem Schism, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0738,1011</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi-Iran Split Mirrors Age-Old Moslem Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 13-14 ``The Sunnis ...'' with 2 grafs to ADD Sunni
belief on heirs to faith.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The animosity between Saudi Arabia and
Iran that has led to their recent diplomatic split is rooted in a
centuries-old schism in the Moslem world between the Sunni and
Shiite sects.
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's 1979 Islamic revolution in Iran,
which is predominantly Shiite, dragged the religious feud into the
20th century, sparking new fears among the conservative,
Sunni-dominated Persian Gulf states and other Arab countries.
   The revolution's triumph in toppling the pro-Western Shah
Mohammed Reza Pahlavi also fueled Islamic fervor among
fundamentalist Sunnis.
   That, along with the vigorous Shiite challenge, has ignited
violence from socialist Syria to monarchist Morocco in the last
decade.
   The Islamic resurgence has brought a religious intensity not
witnessed since the Middle Ages and has perplexed and alarmed the
West.
   While the Saudis cited terrorism and threats for breaking
relations with Tehran on April 27, they mainly were seeking to head
off Iranian-inspired violence in the holy city of Mecca in this
year's annual haj, or pilgrimage.
   More than 400 pilgrims, 275 of them Iranians, were killed in
rioting in Mecca last year that shocked the Moslem world. Iran
vowed revenge and Khomeini called for the overthrow of Saudi
Arabia's royal family.
   The Saudis want to avoid a repetition of the violence this year
by getting Moslem countries to scale down the number of pilgrims
they send. Iran, asked to trim its contingent of the usual 150,000
by about one-third, refuses.
   Instead, Iran has revived calls for an Islamic crusade against
Saudi Arabia and stripping the royal family of custodianship of
Islam's holiest shrines in Mecca, Prophet Mohammed's birthplace,
and in Medina, where he is buried.
   The guardianship of these holy sites is one of the underpinnings
of the Saudi monarchy that gives it political legitimacy in the
eyes of most Moslems.
   The deepening hostility between Iran and Saudi Arabia has been
exacerbated by the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war, in which the Saudis
have supported Arab Iraq against Persian Iran.
   The Arabs and Persians, separated by language and culture, have
been religious rivals since the death of Mohammed, the founder of
Islam, in 632 A.D.
   The Sunnis, who make up more than 90 percent of the world's 850
million Moslems, revere Mohammed as second only to God and view Abu
Bakr, the prophet's father-in-law and the man who became Islam's
first caliph, as his rightful successor.
   The mystical Shiites consider Mohammed's cousin and son-in-law,
Ali, the fourth caliph, and 11 of his descendants to be the true
heirs of the faith. They revere all 12 as imams, or saints, and
believe the 12th imam, Mehdi, will return like a messiah to bring
justice to the world.
   Ali was assassinated in 661 amid a power struggle by two
factions over who would lead the Moslem world following Mohammed's
death.
   Ali's death confirmed the Sunni Umayyad dynasty in power as the
Caliphs, or successors of the prophet. Ali's descendants remained
in perpetual revolt, claiming to be the true Caliphate and refusing
to accept orthodox teachings espoused by the Sunnis.
   Ali's son, Hussein, led one rebellion and was massacred with his
handful of outnumbered followers in the Battle of Karbala, in what
is now Iraq, in 680.
   Ever since, the minority Shiites were considered heretics. Only
in Iran, where for political motives a 16th century shah embraced
Shiitism as the established creed, did the downtrodden sect
flourish.
   Every year, when they mark the death of Hussein, militant
Shiites flagellate themselves with chains and swords in a
passionate celebration of the martyr _ acts which Sunnis regard as
demeaning.
   For Khomeini and his followers, their revolution was the dawn of
a new age of Islamic fundamentalism as a powerful force in the
world, the time of reckoning after 1,300 years of subjugation.
   The revival stems in part from Moslems rebelling against the
Western influence that colonialism brought and oil wealth
intensified in the last two decades, transforming what were feudal
societies and eroding cultural values. In this vacuum,
fundamentalism has taken root.
   Khomeini's belief that Iran is the beacon for a fundamentalist
revival that will sweep the world and his drive to export the
revolution has caused mayhem among the monarchies of the Persian
Gulf who believe themselves vulnerable.
   The Iran-Iraq war has only heightened the passions.
   Tiny Kuwait, which is closest to the war zone and under constant
threat from Iran, has cracked down hard on its Shiite militants
after a chain of terrorist attacks, including the April 5 hijacking
of a Kuwaiti jetliner by Shiite extremists. On Sunday, the
newspaper al-Anbaa called for the government to deport Shiite
Moslems who show allegiance to Iran.
   Shiites comprise about one-fourth of Kuwait's 1.9 million
population. In Bahrain, where Sunnis rule, the Shiites form about
70 percent of the population.
   Seven years ago, Bahraini authorities foiled what apparently was
a Shiite plot aimed at assassinating the ruler, Sheik Isa bin
Sulman Al-Khalifa.
   Fundamentalism inspired by Khomeini's revolution has reared up
further afield.
   Tunisia broke off relations with Tehran last year, alleging Iran
was seeking to foster an Islamic rebellion.
   Fundamentalists assassinated President Anwar Sadat of Egypt in
1980 and remain politically active there.
   Syrian President Hafez Assad crushed a rebellion by the
fundamentalist Moslem Brotherhood in the city of Hama in 1982,
slaughtering as many as 30,000 people and razing much of the city.
   Saudi Arabia's decision to sever relations with Tehran has
increased the polarization between Iran's Shiite zealots and the
Arabs that the Iran-Iraq war has brought.
   But the Saudis also were throwing down the gauntlet to their
Shiite rivals only a few weeks before the haj is due to start, and
that could have dangerous consequences in their feud.
</TEXT>
