<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Poland     05-08 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Poland,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Official Defends Actions Against Strikers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Polish official, responding to Reagan
administration criticism of a crackdown on labor unrest, denied
Sunday that strikers were beaten and said a government that fired
its air traffic controllers should know the difference between a
legal and an illegal strike.
   Lt. Col. Wieslaw Gornicki, Polish government political adviser,
denied news reports and U.S. government allegations of violence
against striking workers at a Krakow steel mill and accused the
news media of exaggerating and inflaming conditions in Poland.
   ``The strike was crushed, but nobody was beaten,'' Gornicki said
in an interview from Warsaw on ABC-TV's ``This Week with David
Brinkley.''
   ``If it all were true what your news media is reporting, we
would have a general strike, a nationwide strike of 10 days or
perhaps three months,'' Gornicki said. At least five strikes have
occurred in Poland in the past two weeks, including one at the
Lenin shipyard where negotiations were continuing between workers
and management.
   Asked about the reported use of percussion grenades to quell the
Krakow strike, which had lasted 10 days, Gornicki said he did not
believe the devices were used but added, ``I cannot rule it out.''
   Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead condemned the
reported violence Saturday and announced that U.S. backing for
Poland's economic recovery program would remain frozen until the
program wins popular support. The White House twice last week also
issued statements condemning the government's reported use of force
against strikes backed by the outlawed Solidarity labor movement.
   Gornicki did not directly respond to the official U.S.
criticism. But he said, ``You know, a country which not long ago
had a certain experience with its air traffic controllers union ...
should make a clear-cut difference between a strike which is legal
... and wildcat strikes, which as you know very well are illegal.''
   President Reagan fired striking air traffic controllers after
what the government said was an illegal strike in 1981.
   Gornicki said strikes represent problems with adaptation to
``the new style of our economic life.''
   U.S. officials, including Vice President George Bush during a
visit to Poland last September, had applauded Polish steps toward
economic reform prior to the current unrest. In March, a U.S.
ambassador, John R. Davis, was posted in Warsaw for the first time
in five years.
</TEXT>
