<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Refusenik     05-08 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Refusenik,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refusenik Tufeld Receives Passport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish refusenik Vladimir Tufeld said Sunday he
had received a passport from Soviet authorities and would fly to
the United States to be with his ill wife in several days.
   Tufeld, a 60-year-old electronics engineer who had been refused
permission to emigrate for almost 11 years, said in a telephone
interview he received his passport from the Moscow visa office
Saturday. He said he planned to leave for New York on May 13.
   His 57-year-old wife, Izolda, was granted permission in late
December to travel to the United States for surgery to remove a
brain tumor. She remains in Johns Hopkins hospital in Baltimore.
   Officials of the Soviet Ministry of General Machine Building
told Tufeld that he could not leave the country because he had
access to state secrets when he worked at an electronics factory in
the 1970s.
   But he said officials told him in late April they would allow
him to leave temporarily to be with his wife. Tufeld said Soviet
officials did not put any limit on the length of time he may be
abroad.
