<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Dissidents 1stLd-Writethru a0746 05-08 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Dissidents, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0746,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Groups Challenging Official Monopoly Meet in Moscow</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with 20 people reportedly
detained. PICKS up 11th graf, `Many dissident ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet police on Sunday tried to interrupt
meetings of scores of dissidents seeking to challenge the supremacy
of the Communist Party and detained 20 people as they left one of
the gatherings, dissidents said.
   Editors of 30 non-official journals hoping to break the
government monopoly on publishing also met in Moscow to formalize
their cooperation by establishing the Independent Publications Club.
   On Saturday, 148 people attended an initial meeting to form an
alternative political party called the Democratic Union. On Sunday,
they broke into groups to discuss the party's political platform
and socio-economic and organizational questions.
   Yevgeniya Debryanskaya, who hosted the meeting about the group's
political platform, said police arrived at her north Moscow
apartment in about 30 cars Sunday evening and tried to enter.
   About 50 people were jammed in Ms. Debryanskaya's living room,
thrashing out the group's political goals.
   Ms. Debryanskaya said the group refused to let officers in, but
20 people were detained as they left. She said in a telephone
interview that she did not know what happened to them, but noted
that authorities often hold people for several hours and then
release them.
   Smaller groups discussed the party's organization and
socio-economic policies at two other Moscow apartments.
   Igor Tsarkov, leader of the organizational meeting, said a
Moscow city official accompanied by police arrived at the meeting
and asked that the group of 15 disband.
   Police asked to check their documents, but the participants
refused and police eventually left, Tsarkov said.
   Valentin Eliseyedko, head of the group on socio-economic
problems, said police also visited that meeting and checked
documents, but otherwise did not interfere.
   Ms. Debryanskaya said in an interview earlier Sunday that a
committee of 15 people had drafted political principles calling for:
   _ Multi-party, parliamentary democracy;
   _ A new constitution, replacing the current document that makes
the Communist Party the ``leading and guiding force'' of Soviet
society;
   _ Independent trade unions; and
   _ Withdrawal of Soviet soldiers from Eastern European countries
and from the western Ukraine and the Baltic states, which Ms.
Debryanskaya said the group considers to be under Soviet occupation.
   The meetings of the Democratic Union and the independent
publishers group were were notable for the number of people they
drew to Moscow. Authorities have not broken up previous efforts to
hold dissident conferences, but they have closed conference
facilities and prevented some people from traveling to them.
   Many dissident groups and independent publications have sprung
up since hundreds of political prisoners were freed in 1987.
   Authorities in the past have crushed efforts to form an
opposition to the Communist Party, and despite his reform effort,
Mikhail S. Gorbachev has given no indication the party will
tolerate any opposition.
   Ms. Debryanskaya said Gorbachev will allow the group to exist if
he is serious about reforms. ``Arguments and disagreements are
normal in society,'' she said.
   But any such group also faces enormous difficulties in a vast
country where the government controls printing facilities and
authorities can detain or intimidate dissidents and disrupt mail
and telephone calls.
   On Saturday, dissident sources said police surrounded the
apartment building across the street from the government offices of
the Russian republic, where the first meeting was held, but did not
break it up.
   Ms. Debryanskaya said her group will make a formal declaration
seeking official recognition of the Democratic Union and transmit
it to Moscow city authorities.
   She has been active in a group supporting greater trust between
East and West, and a second group calling itself ``Democracy and
Humanism.''
   Former political prisoners Sergei Grigoryants and Lev Timofeyev,
and other publishers of independent journals from Moscow,
Leningrad, Riga, Lvov, Pskov and Kuybyshev decided at their weekend
gatherings to form a library to preserve and help disseminate their
publications.
   Thirty publications emphasizing such topics as political
commentary, religion and women's issues were represented,
participants said. A similar meeting was held in Leningrad last
fall, and the group agreed to hold another large conference in
Moscow in October.
   Some of the publications have sought official approval, but none
has been given.
   Participants in the editors' gathering said police checked
documents of people who arrived at the south Moscow apartment on
Saturday, but no police or plainclothes officers were visible
Sunday.
</TEXT>
