<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CatholicMothers     05-08 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Catholic Mothers,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mothers Day Sets Stage For Vigil Seeking Greater Role, Priesthood
For Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters denouncing the Roman Catholic Church's
``hypocrisy'' of honoring women on Mother's Day while denying them
the priesthood staged a peaceful vigil Sunday outside Holy Name
Cathedral.
   A smaller group of demonstrators, some carrying pictures of Pope
John Paul II, gathered to reinforce church teachings that women
cannot be priests.
   About 40 members and supporters of a group called Chicago
Catholic Women stood outside the cathedral, home pulpit of Cardinal
Joseph Bernardin, holding signs including one which said: ``We want
a church for our daughters.''
   The demonstrators, who included a handful of men, passed out
fliers urging parishioners to boycott regular services and to
attend an alternate service later at a North Side women's center.
   ``There's something to tradition,'' said Gerry Gorman, 35, who
was carrying her 10-month-old son, Gabriel. ``There's also
something to ending an unjust system.''
   Another demonstrator was Debra Graves, 32, of Woodridge, who
said she has a master's degree in divinity from Harvard and would
likely go into the priesthood if allowed.
   ``I'm ready,'' she said. ``My church is not.''
   Hundreds of parishioners and visitors attended the morning
Mother's Day Mass inside Holy Name while the demonstrators stood
outside.
   Nanci Mayhoefer, 43, of Chicago was among about 10 demonstrators
against ordination of women.
   ``Tradition is a very strong part of our church,'' Mrs.
Mayhoefer said. In performing part of the church service, the
priest ``takes the place of Christ,'' and a woman can't play that
role, she said.
   Ms. Gorman, of Chicago, said the vigil was planned because the
issue of women and the church is ``tearing the church apart'' and
was not given serious consideration by bishops who attended last
fall's Synod on the Laity at the Vatican.
   Her group's flier said the church shows ``hypocrisy'' on
Mother's Day.
   ``This is the day on which the institutional church `honors' its
women,'' it said. ``By our absence we hope to demonstrate our
frustration with such tokenism.''
   Marie Knoll, a spokeswoman for the Archdiocese of Chicago,
issued a statement on the issue before Sunday's protest.
   ``The recent pastoral letter by the U.S. bishops responding to
the concerns of women clearly acknowledges that more needs to be
done to recognize and incorporate the insights and talents of women
as partners in the church,'' she said.
   Irene McCartin, 42, a parishioner from Olympia Fields, seemed to
agree with the archdiocese view.
   ``For some families, it's really one time to get together,'' she
said of Mother's Day. The demonstration, she said, ``takes away
from it.''
   But another parishioner, Barbara Malewicki, 46, of Lansing, was
not offended. ``I think there's merit in what they have to say, and
it should be talked about, not dismissed,'' she said.
</TEXT>
