<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MultipleKillings     05-08 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Killings,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused in 16 Slayings to Be Tried Monday for Two of Them</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused in 16 deaths, including the
Christmastime slaughter of 14 relatives, will go to trial first for
the two killings outside his family.
   R. Gene Simmons, 47, a retired Air Force master sergeant, is
charged with two counts of capital murder in the Dec. 28 shooting
spree in Russellville in which six people were shot by a gunman
wielding two .22 caliber pistols. Two of the victims died.
   In his trial, which begins Monday, Simmons could be sentenced to
die or to life in prison without parole if convicted of either
count of capital murder. He also will be tried on five counts of
attempted capital murder and one of kidnapping.
   The defense will ask Circuit Judge John Patterson to dismiss the
attempted capital murder counts on grounds that, under Arkansas
law, they are superseded by the capital murder counts, according to
defense attorney John Harris.
   Following the shooting spree, 14 members of Simmons family were
found slaughtered. Charges from the slaying of the family are to be
tried later.
   The 16 deaths made it one of the worst mass slayings in American
history.
   The case was moved to Ozark after the defense argued that there
had been so much pretrial publicity that it would be difficult to
get an unprejudiced jury in Russellville, 47 miles west of here.
   Harris declined to say whether Simmons would testify.
   The attorney said Sunday that he had no plans ``at this time''
to raise insanity as a defense. Tests on Simmons found no evidence
of a problem such as a brain tumor that could have affected his
behavior.
   After his arrest, Simmons was was found by doctors to be legally
sane and thus able to stand trial.
   Moments before he surrendered Dec. 28, police said, the gunman
told his hostage: ``I've gotten everybody who wanted to hurt me.
I've come to do what I wanted to do. It's all over now.''
   Simmons will be on trial for the deaths of Kathy C. Kendrick,
24, who police say once spurned Simmons' romantic advances, and of
James D. Chaffin, 33, who police say was a chance victim.
   Miss Kendrick was shot in the head at a Russellville law office
where she was a legal secretary. Chaffin was slain at an oil
company where the gunman wounded the oil company owner.
   To be tried later are two capital murder charges, one accusing
Simmons of killing seven relatives, the other accusing him of
killing seven other relatives. There are two groups of seven
because authorities believe the killings took place at different
times.
   After Simmons was arrested, sheriff's deputies found the bodies
of five relatives, including two of his children and their spouses.
Four of the victims had been shot and the other victim, Simmons'
11-year-old granddaughter, had been strangled. They apparently died
after they arrived for a Christmas season family gathering, police
said.
   The next day, police dug into a shallow, kerosene-soaked grave
and found seven bodies, including those of Simmons' other children
and his wife, Becky. She had told family members in a letter ``I am
a prisoner here, and the kids, too.''
   Police said that some of these victims had been shot, others
strangled, apparently before Christmas _ gift packages were
unopened beneath the Christmas tree.
   Police also found the bodies of two infant boys in garbage sacks
in the trunks of abandoned cars on Simmons property. They were
strangled.
   The gun that killed Miss Kendrick and Chaffin had been used to
kill some of Simmons' relatives, state ballistics experts said.
</TEXT>
