<HEAD>Police Arrest 9-Year-Old For Alleged Cocaine Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old boy was arrested for allegedly
selling cocaine supplied to him by adults, police said.
   ``Lots of kids sell drugs,'' the unidentified boy reportedly
told officers after being taken into custody Saturday.
   ``For every five buyers, they (suppliers) give me $50,'' he said.
   Before he was led away, the youth pointed out his alleged
employers, police said. Hector Ramos, Dianilo Gonzalez and Juan
Rivera Ramos face charges of conspiring to violate drug laws, said
Jill Reilly, a police spokeswoman.
   Reilly said the boy was charged with possession of a Class B
substance and released to his mother. His name was not released
because of his age.
   Police went to the city's Dorchester section area Friday night
after receiving reports of a young boy who was selling drugs and
carrying a gun.
   The boy was spotted in front of an apartment building and turned
to flee when the officers approached, but he stopped in his tracks
when ordered to halt, Reilly said.
   ``I don't have a gun, just this package,'' the boy told officers
as he reached inside his pants pocket and brought out a package of
what he said was cocaine.
   Before being taken to the station, the boy pointed to three men
getting out of a car nearby and said: ``Those are the ones who gave
me the cocaine to sell.''
