<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Hungary     05-08 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Hungary,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Meets With Hungarian Leaders In Budapest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres met with
Hungarian leaders in Budapest Sunday during the first visit by a
high-ranking Israeli official to the communist country, the Foreign
Ministry announced.
   Hungary, along with most other Eastern European nations, severed
ties with Israel after the 1967 Middle East war, but last year
Israel and Hungary established low-level diplomatic contacts.
   Peres met with Prime Minister Karoly Grosz and Foreign Minister
Peter Varkony, Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesman Ehud Gol told The
Associated Press.
   Gol said Peres and the Hungarian officials discussed the
Arab-Israeli conflict and bilateral ties, including economic issues
and tourism. He did not elaborate.
   The Israeli Foreign Ministry kept the visit secret until the
meetings were completed.
   Hungary's national news agency MTI issued no report on the
meeting and phone calls went unanswered at Israel's economic
interest section at the Swiss Embassy in Budapest.
   Peres flew from Israel to Zurich, Switzerland, on Sunday
morning, leaving 12 hours before his scheduled departure for Madrid
where he was to attend the Socialist International.
   During the Socialist International, Peres, head of the socialist
Labor Party, will meet with Soviet officials, including members of
the Communist Party's Central Committee, Gol said.
   Peres has told Israel television he might meet with Soviet
officials during his trip and he said he hoped to discuss a
possible renewal of ties with the Kremlin that were severed in 1967.
   Israel's relations with the Soviet bloc have been improving
steadily in the past few years.
   In September, Hungary became the second Eastern European country
after Poland to resume limited diplomatic ties with the Jewish
state.
</TEXT>
