<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0758 05-08 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0758,0871</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fighting Between Shiites Rages, Ending Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE casualty figures. Pickup 3rd
graf pvs ``Police said...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias ended a
16-hour truce Sunday, fighting each other with tanks, mortars and
truck-mounted rocket launchers in battles that killed seven people
and wounded 25, police said.
   The toll from three days of fighting rose to 89 dead and 242
wounded following the breakdown of an Iranian- and Syrian-brokered
cease-fire.
   Police said hostilities broke out in south Beirut's densely
populated districts of Ghobeiri, Bir el-Abed and Hay Madi and
quickly spread to five adjacent neighborhoods.
   The fighting has included gunbattles inside a hospital, where a
doctor said militiamen forced surgeons to operate on dead comrades
``to bring them back to life.''
   Justice Minister Nabih Berri's pro-Syrian Amal militia and the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, accused each other of
breaking the cease-fire.
   Hezbollah is believed to be an umbrella for extremist factions
holding many of the 18 kidnapped foreigners in Lebanon, some of
whom are reportedly held in the embattled slums. It was not known
if the fighting had any effect on the captives.
   The fighting was touched off Friday by a pre-dawn ambush in
which four Amal militiamen were killed. Amal blamed Hezbollah.
   The thud of explosions and bursts of gunfire resounded across
the city Sunday. Both sides mounted grenade-throwing assaults on
each other's positions.
   Several apartment buildings were ablaze, but fire engines could
not enter the area because of the fighting.
   Both sides went on a kidnapping spree, abducting at least 20
civilians suspected of sympathizing with either side. Police had
said more than 100 other civilians have been abducted since the
outbreak of the slums war.
   An Amal communique charged Hezbollah gunmen were sniping at
residential neighborhoods from rooftops of apartment buildings in
the sprawling Shiyah district, and warned that this would spread
the fighting.
   Shiyah abuts Beirut's Green Line, which has sliced the capital
into Moslem and Christian sectors since the 1975 outbreak of
Lebanon's civil war.
   As the guns roared, Syria dispatched its military intelligence
chief in Lebanon, Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kenaan, to west Beirut on an
apparent mission to reinstate the cease-fire.
   Kenaan went into conference with Berri at his sandbagged
residence in west Beirut's Barbour neighborhood, about five miles
from the fighting.
   State-run Radio Beirut said Kenaan also met acting Prime
Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, and Shiite Parliament Speaker
Hussein Husseini.
   A coalition of the nation's senior Sunni and Shiite religious
leaders called on Syria to send troops into the slums.
   Syria deployed 7,500 troops in west Beirut on Feb. 22, 1987 to
curb the reign of feuding militias. The slums are outside the
jurisdiction of that contingent.
   The short-lived lull, which began about midnight Saturday,
allowed Red Cross and civil defense rescuers to evacuate scores of
trapped victims. Hospitals issued urgent appeals for blood
donations.
   An Iranian mission headed by Deputy Foreign Minister Hussein
Sheikholeslam also was trying to negotiate a new truce, Radio
Beirut said.
   During the lull Sunday morning, the slums' estimated 250,000
inhabitants of the slums began venturing from their basements and
bomb shelters where they had been trapped for more than 50 hours.
   ``What have I done to deserve all this?'' asked Ali Shabshoul,
34, a grocer, whose shop in Bir el-Abed was reduced to a pile of
rubble by shellfire. His wife and two children stood crying beside
him.
   Nabil Alameh, while taking stock of the damage to his perfume
shop in an Amal-controlled neighborhood in Ghobeiri, asked: ``Who
is going to compensate me?''
   When told that ``Allah'' (God) would, he retorted icily, ``Allah
or his party?'' an apparent reference to Hezbollah.
   Many residents hurriedly packed up beds, mattresses and clothes,
and drove away from the slums. Others installed new doors on
damaged shops and houses.
   A doctor at al-Sahel hospital, which has received more than 100
casualties from both sides, said Hezbollah and Amal had clashed
inside the building.
   ``We have been forced many times to flee and abandon victims
because of frequent gunfights in the emergency ward,'' said the
doctor, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   She said doctors also had been forced at by frenzied gunmen to
operate on dead comrades, ``telling us at gunpoint to bring them
back to life.''
   Police said Hezbollah appears to have made substantial
territorial gains in the fighting around the Ghobeiri district that
is home to the party's mentor, Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah.
But each side held its ground elsewhere.
   During the lull in the fighting, Berri issued a statement
accusing Hezbollah of turning the slums into a ``a nest of terror
where kidnapped foreigners are held hostage.''
   ``You are a war criminal,'' retorted Hezbollah in a statement
released in west Beirut and addressed to Berri. ``Only spies of the
Great Satan (the United States) call us terrorists.''
   In a four-day confrontation last month, Amal crushed Hezbollah
throughout south Lebanon. Police said 62 people were killed and 150
wounded.
</TEXT>
