<HEAD>`Incoherent' Juror Replaced In Fifth Day Of Life-Or-Death
Deliberations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, Lawson has...', to UPDATE with jury recessing
for the day. Picks up 13th graf, `Coleman, Carl...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A juror who ``was not coherent'' was
replaced with an alternate Sunday during a fifth day of
deliberations on whether Wayne Carl Coleman should die for the 1973
slayings of six members of one family.
   Judge Hugh Lawson excused the juror after a court deputy said
the woman was not capable of continuing in Coleman's murder retrial
for the Alday family deaths.
   The juror who was replaced appeared before the judge.
   Much of her testimony was inaudible. But she was heard to say
several times: ``They put a bug in my ear. Remember Mary Alday.''
   Mary Alday was the last of the six victims in the killing spree
in Seminole County on May 14, 1973. After five Alday men were shot
to death one by one at Jerry Alday's home, Mrs. Alday, Jerry's
wife, was taken to a nearby field where she was raped and killed.
   A deputy assigned to watch the sequestered jurors told the judge
that the juror ``was mumbling nonsense. She was not coherent. She
is not physically or mentally capable to continue.''
   The woman was the second juror to be replaced.
   Defense attorney Tom West moved again Sunday, as he has before,
for Lawson to declare the jury deadlocked. In such a case, Coleman,
whose original death sentence for the slayings was overturned on
appeal, automatically would be sentenced to life in prison. He has
served 15 years on his original conviction.
   Lawson again rejected the motion.
   The jurors convicted Coleman on six counts of murder last
Monday. On Wednesday, they began deliberating whether he should be
sentenced to death or to life in prison.
   Attorneys in the case believe a minority of the jurors are
holding out for a life sentence.
   Lawson has given no indication when he might halt deliberations;
on Saturday, he recharged the jurors and told them he wants them to
reach a decision. After the Sunday court session, the jury resumed
deliberations for a time before recessing for the day at
midafternoon.
   Coleman, Carl Isaacs and George Elder Dungee were convicted of
murder and sentenced to death in 1974 for the May 14, 1973,
killings of Ned Alday, his brother Aubrey, Ned's sons Jimmy, Jerry
and Chester, and Jerry's wife, Mary.
   The convictions were overturned by a federal appeals court in
1985 because of pretrial publicity.
   Isaacs was convicted a second time in January and again
sentenced to death. Dungee is to be retried later in Columbus.
</TEXT>
