<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PhilippinesAid     05-08 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines Aid,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Getting Behind Philippines Aid Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is putting together
a $10 billion international aid program for the Philippines after
asking Congress for a decrease in direct U.S. assistance to the
financially troubled ally.
   The five-year plan, originally proposed by two Democratic and
two Republican members of Congress, would gather new money and
benefits for the Philippines from other nations, including Japan,
Australia and European countries.
   Officials have not indicated what the U.S. share would be.
   The proposal, patterned after the 1947 Marshall Plan to rescue
Western Europe after World War II, is being put together while U.S.
negotiators in Manila face demands for big increases in payments
for the use of key Air Force and Navy bases in the Philippines.
   Philippine Foreign Minister Raul Manglapus has said U.S.
``rent'' for the bases should be increased from the current $180
million a year to as much as $1.2 billion annually and should be in
addition to any other aid. Both congressional and administration
officials have said that kind of money likely would not be
available.
   Congress last year appropriated $347 million for the government
of President Corazon Aquino. The Reagan administration has asked
that that be cut to $257 million in the next fiscal year budget.
   A U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Saturday the administration is moving toward announcement of the
international aid plan.
   The administration also plans to send a high-level special
emissary to the Philippines to dramatize its concern for conditions
in the country, The Washington Post reported on Sunday.
   The newspaper said a congressional delegation might accompany
the official, who would deliver a pledge of top-level support and
consult with Aquino on details of the program.
   The original proposal by Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and
Richard Lugar, R-Ind., and Reps. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., and Jack
Kemp, R-N.Y., called for at least $1 billion a year in new
international aid to Aquino's government and proposed that a
prominent American be appointed by the president to lead the
effort. The Post report said such an appointment was likely.
   The Philippines economy has been showing signs of increased
health since a popular uprising in February 1986 ended two decades
of authoritarian rule by Ferdinand E. Marcos and installed Mrs.
Aquino. But the government has had to use much of its income to
meet interest payments on its $26 billion foreign debt.
   The Post, citing unidentified sources, said the aid plan would
include debt relief in the form of reduced payments or debt-equity
swaps, trade preferences to encourage Philippine exports, and
private investments from international financial institutions and
businesses, in addition to direct aid.
</TEXT>
