<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Violence,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethnic Violence Spreads In Karachi, At Least 30 Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunfire and streetfighting flared again
Sunday between ethnic Pakistanis and Indian immigrants in
Pakistan's largest city and at least 14 people were killed,
officials reported.
   The deaths brought the number of people slain in 10 days of
clashes to at least 30. A traffic accident in west Karachi April 29
led to riots in the eastern and northern sections of this city of 7
million people.
   Both groups compete for blue-collar jobs in a city with high
unemployment.
   Sunday's dead included at least four policemen killed when
militant Pathans, who trace their roots to northern Pakistan,
attacked police headquarters in three working-class neighborhoods,
according to the official APP news agency.
   It said the casualties included ``mohajirs'' _ Indian Moslems
who emigrated to Pakistan when India was partitioned in 1947 _ but
gave no figures.
   Karachi, a port city on the Indian Ocean, has had ethnic
violence for years. Several hundred people perished in riots in
late 1986.
   Traffic accidents and other minor incidents often erupt into
street battles.
   The troubled areas were reported calm Sunday night as army
troops moved in to impose an indefinite curfew.
