<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KochPoll     05-08 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koch Poll,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor's Approval Rating Drops, According to New York Newsday Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch's approval rating has
dropped sharply because of his controversial comments during the
recent New York primary, with his standing suffering most among
blacks, according to a poll released Sunday.
   The poll, conducted last week for New York Newsday by the Gallup
Organization, found 43 percent approved of Koch's performance as
mayor while 42 percent disapproved and 15 percent had no opinion.
   It was the first of five polls conducted for Newsday in the past
year that gave Koch an approval rating of less than 50 percent. The
previous poll in December 1987 gave him a favorable rating of 55
percent.
   Only 21 percent of blacks and 44 percent of Hispanics gave Koch
a favorable rating, down from 44 percent and 56 percent,
respectively, in December.
   Fifty-three percent of whites approved of the mayor, including
61 percent of Jews, down from 59 percent and 65 percent,
respectively, in December.
   During the campaign for last month's primary, Koch said Jews and
supporters of Israel ``would have to be crazy'' to vote for
Jackson, who has met in the past with leaders of the Palestine
Liberation Organization. He also said Jackson's proposed policies
would leave the country bankrupt and defenseless.
   Fifty-two percent of those polled said Koch's rhetoric
heightened racial tensions and 39 percent said they were less
likely to vote for him as a result.
   Regarding the 1989 mayoral race, 49 percent said Koch should not
seek re-election to a fourth term and 40 percent said he should. In
December, 45 percent said the mayor should seek re-election and 44
percent said he should not.
   Only 18 percent of blacks thought Koch should run for
re-election, down from 40 percent in December, while 40 percent of
Hispanics said he should run, down from 47 percent. Forty-nine
percent of whites said he should run, including 59 percent of Jews,
up from 47 percent and 56 percent, respectively, in December.
   The telephone poll surveyed 1,033 city residents and had a
margin of error of plus or minus four percentage points.
</TEXT>
