<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Elections,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It's Off To The Horse Races After Voting In Two Texas Counties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texans have voted to authorize horse racing and
pari-mutuel betting in Dallas and Lubbock counties, and in one
small town's mayoral race a husband and wife ran against each other
and both lost to a write-in vote.
   In unofficial returns from all precincts, Dallas County voters
approved pari-mutuel betting 42,198 to 32,830, or 56 percent to 44
percent.
   Lubbock County voters approved pari-mutuel 18,939, or 52
percent, to 17,541, or 48 percent in complete returns.
   In Melvin, a West Texas town of 202 people, Florence and Nestor
Perez, both Republicans, faced each other on the ballot but were
defeated by write-in candidate J.T. Sparks, the incumbent
Democratic mayor.
   Sparks, who changed his mind about running after the filing
deadline, got 28 votes, Florence Perez got 27 and Nestor Perez got
7.
   The Lubbock racing vote was a reversal of last November's
election, when pari-mutuel won statewide despite a negative vote in
the West Texas county.
   A leader of the anti-gambling forces said more money and
stronger campaigning probably wouldn't have turned the tide.
   ``If we had been more visible it would just have increased the
turnout,'' said Sue Cox, executive director of Texans Who Care,
adding that greater numbers would probably work in favor of
pro-gambling efforts.
   Dallas voters also approved by more than a 2-to-1 margin a
proposal to build a new 12-story jail tower that would add 2,304
bunks to the county's jail capacity.
   Also Saturday, the city that doesn't want to be elected three
candidates who agree with that sentiment. Crystal Beach residents,
who voted in 1987 to disincorporate, elected three men who promised
to put the community of 1,045 back under the jurisdiction of
Galveston County.
</TEXT>
