<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CourthouseMurders     05-08 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Courthouse Murders,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Trial Takes Place at Scene of the Crime</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ST. JOE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection for the murder trial of
a man who allegedly gunned down a judge and two others during a
divorce hearing will start Monday at the scene of the crime.
   Clyde M. Melvin faces three first-degree murder counts in the
July 28, 1987 shooting deaths at the Gulf County Courthouse.
Circuit Judge Wilson Lamar Bailey, 64, of Blountstown; Panama City
lawyer Tom Ingles, 43, who represented Melvin's ex-wife in divorce
proceedings; and Peggy White Paulk, 55, of Panama City Beach, his
ex-wife's sister, died.
   If convicted, Melvin could be sentenced to death or life in
prison without parole for at least 25 years.
   Melvin, 63, also is charged with attempted first-degree murder
in the shooting of his ex-wife, Eleanor Inez Huckeba, 59. She
suffered a gunshot wound to the head and has since recovered.
   The defendant, a former security guard, was wounded in the neck
by Gulf County Sheriff Al Harrison during the courthouse shootout.
   The selection of a 12-member jury is expected to take two days.
The crimes have received intense publicity, and court officials
have subpoenaed 450 prospective jurors in their effort to get an
impartial jury.
   The shootings began during a hearing on actions related to the
couple's Nov. 4, 1986, divorce, including a contempt motion against
Melvin for allegedly falling behind in his $350 monthly alimony
payments.
   Neither State Attorney Jim Appleman of Marianna nor Melvin's
court-appointed defense lawyer, Henry Barksdale, would talk about
the case.
   Circuit Judge Carl Harper, who spent most of his judicial career
in Palm Beach County, was called out of retirement to preside. He
has plenty of experience in handling highly publicized trials,
including the Roxanne Pulitzer divorce case and the murder trial of
Robert Spearman, who was convicted of hiring hit men advertised in
Soldier of Fortune magazine to kill his wife and committed suicide
in his prison cell last week.
</TEXT>
