<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-88 1923EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bulwer-Lytton 1stLd-Writethru a0784 05-08 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bulwer-Lytton, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0784,0717</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Literary `Creme de Dreck' of Writing Goes To...</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with comment from winner. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs. Spelling of moulding cq in 11th graf. EMBARGOED by
source until 9 p.m. EDT Sunday</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The best of the worst, the tops of the
lowest, the most awful assaults on the art of writing were honored
Sunday in the annual Bulwer-Lytton Fiction Contest.
   The top prize, the ``creme de la dreck,'' went to Rachel
Sheeley, 20, a journalism student at Franklin College in Indiana.
   ``I'd hate to say that bad writing comes naturally, but my
creative juices were flowing that day,'' Sheeley said in a
telephone interview Sunday. ``You have to get into a bad frame of
mind.''
   She said she is a would-be novelist, ``But I'm a pretty bad
procrastinator, so for now I want to go into newspaper writing and
have a deadline to write for.''
   Whether a boon or bane for her career, the prize came from San
Jose State University Professor Scott Rice, founder and ``grand
panjandrum'' of the literary disgrace he calls ``the Baltimore
Orioles of literature.''
   Despite the humor that surrounds its awarding, Rice stresses
that the competition is not a ``joke-writing contest. It really
takes a very good writer to deliberately write bad.''
   The contest trashes the battered memory of 19th century English
writer Edward George Earle Bulwer-Lytton. His turgid style is
captured in the opening line to one of his novels, later enshrined
by Snoopy, the erudite pooch in the comic strip Peanuts: ``It was a
dark and stormy night ...''
   Rice notes that Bulwer-Lytton also is remembered for such
ringing cliches as ``The pen is mightier than the sword'' and ``The
Great Unwashed.''
   This year's No-Ribbon Panel of Undistinguished Judges examined
more than 11,000 entries, searching for the most miserable, least
readable and rottenest lead sentence to the crummiest novel
imaginable.
   This awful thing submitted by Miss Sheeley brought her to the
top _ or the bottom _ of the heap:
   ``Like an expensive sports car, fine-tuned and well-built,
Portia was sleek, shapely and gorgeous, her red jumpsuit moulding
her body, which was as warm as the seatcovers in July, her hair as
dark as new tires, her eyes flashing like bright hubcaps, and her
lips dewy as the beads of fresh rain on the hood; she was a woman
driven _ fueled by a single accelerant _ and she needed a man, a
man who wouldn't shift from his views, a man to steer her along the
right road: a man like Alf Romeo.''
   Rice said the contest is a gentle reminder to the world of
letters that it is OK to lighten up, forget the grammar books for a
minute and have some fun, to ``approach the language recreationally
as well as practically.''
   For her effort, Sheeley wins a word processor.
   Awards were also made in selected categories.
   Brian W. Holmes of San Jose, Calif, won in puns: ``Once a month,
when the moon is full, Reverend Jim Bleaker and his lovely wife
Teddi invite members of the church to the parsonage for an evening
of hymn singing, followed by cookies, tea, and a frenzied orgy on
the lawn outside, making sure, of course, to take all the usual
precautions for safe sects.''
   Joan Mazulelwicz of Liverpool, N.Y., won for purple prose: ``The
silent snow fell relentlessly, unceasingly, mercilessly from the
sordid, sullied surreality of the sky as if some enormous, ethereal
diner were shaking grated parmesan on the great, soggy meatball
that was earth.''
   Michael Stratford, Miles City, Mont., won for science fiction:
``Shirley doubted that her alien escort, composed as he was of
vegetable matter, seaweed, and a thick coating of swampy muck,
would be a suitable date for the Intergalactic kegger, but he
turned out to be a real FUNGI.''
   R. B. Nelson, Nottinghamshire, England, won for detective novel:
``With the radio squawking that a 4711 was in progress at 37th and
127th, Murphy knocked car 495 into 3rd and headed up 5th at 70,
little reckoning, as he thumbed his .38, that this would be the day
when his number came up.''
</TEXT>
