<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Autos-MarketShare     05-08 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Autos-Market Share,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Drop Predicted In U.S. Makers' Share of Auto Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. car companies will see their share of the
domestic auto market fall sharply in the next two years as Japanese
companies increase their production here, a study has concluded.
   The management consulting firm of Booz, Allen & Hamilton Inc. of
New York predicted that domestic companies' share of the U.S. auto
market would fall to 56 percent in 1990 from 68 percent last year,
the Detroit News reported Sunday from Washington.
   Japan's auto makers should hold more than 30 percent of the U.S.
market by 1990, the newspaper quoted the study as forecasting.
   The firm's industry analysts estimated Japanese-based companies
would be building about 2.2 million cars a year in U.S. plants by
1990, the newspaper said. That equals the number of cars that the
Japanese export to the United States annually under current
voluntary restraints.
   Honda Motor Co., Toyota Motor Corp., Nissan Motor Corp. and
Mazda Motor Corp. build cars in the United States and three more
Japanese companies plan to start production here by 1990.
   As a result of the competition, General Motors Corp., Ford Motor
Co. and Chrysler Corp. will see their share of the U.S. market
shrink, the study said.
   ``It's going to be more and more difficult to define what is a
U.S. company,'' the News quoted James Mateyka, a vice president of
Booz, Allen in Bethesda, Md., as saying.
   ``After Honda (North America Inc.) adds its engine and
transmission plants (in the United States) will it be less American
than Ford or GM?'' he asked. Honda has a final assembly plant in
Marysville, Ohio, and builds some engines in a former motorcycle
factory also in Ohio.
   The study also predicted that new Japanese auto plants will add
about 30,000 jobs by 1990, but not all will be unionized, the
newspaper reported.
</TEXT>
