<1ST_LINE>r i AM-JapanQuake     05-08 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan Quake,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earthquake Rocks Northern Japan, No Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake hit Japan's northernmost main island
of Hokkaido Monday morning. Police said they had no reports of
damage or casualties.
   The Central Meteorological Agency said the quake registered 5.2
on the Richter scale and struck at 7:44 a.m. _ 6:44 p.m. Sunday
EDT. It said the quake was centered in Hokkaido's Hidaka mountain
range.
   Monday's tremor followed a strong earthquake that measured 6.4
on the Richter and rocked Hokkaido Saturday.
   In that quake, which was centered off the coast of the island,
local trains were temporarily halted while tracks were inspected
but there was no serious damage.
   There have been two major earthquakes in Hokkaido in the past 35
years. A quake in 1968 killed 52 people.
   The Richter scale measures the magnitude of a quake according to
ground motion as recorded on seismographs. An earthquake
registering 5 can cause considerable damage and one of six is
capable of causing severe damage. A reading of 7 indicates a major
quake. Each increase of one number represents a tenfold increase in
magnitude.
</TEXT>
