<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0783 05-08 0803</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0783,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Attacks Bush `Name-calling'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4 new grafs for 9th graf pvs, bgng: ``He was ...'' to
UPDATE with Jackson comments on Bush-Noriega charges; Picks up 10th
graf pvs, bgng: ``Neither Bush ...''; This stands as the
AM-Political Rdp; the other candidates had no campaign appearances.
Note language, 4th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse
Jackson delivered a fresh attack on George Bush Sunday, saying the
vice president has ``started to panic.''
   Last week, Bush referred to Jackson as a ``hustler from
Chicago.'' Jackson has been excoriating the apparent Republican
nominee ever since.
   ``Now as we get closer, the opposition hears our footprints and
begins to panic,'' Jackson said. ``Vice President Bush has begun to
panic and has begun to call me names. ... He's panicking with
indecision. He's panicking with selective memory.''
   ``Why would anyone resort to name-calling?'' Jackson said. ``A
combination of constipation of the brain, deafness of ideas and
diarrhea of the mouth.''
   Bush made the ``hustler'' remark on Friday as he campaigned in
Lincoln, Neb. His campaign staff said there was ``nothing
derogatory'' intended in the remark. Spokesman Stephen Hart later
said it was meant as a comment on how hard Jackson has worked.
   Jackson was not mollified.
   ``He's trapped in an unholy triangle between the Ayatollah,
Noriega and Meese,'' he said of Bush, referring to Iranian leader
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio
Noriega and Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   Jackson's comments came as he was here delivering a graduation
address for his alma mater, North Carolina A&T State University.
Jackson graduated from the college in 1964.
   Campaigning later Sunday in West Virginia, which holds its
primary on Tuesday, Jackson reacted strongly to reports that Bush
had been briefed three years ago about drug trafficking by Noriega.
   ``The reason Mr. Bush has not led the charge to fight drugs is
because he knew of the administration's dealings with the drug
dealers,'' Jackson told reporters at Huntington's Tri-State
Airport. ``We must be leaders in an aggressive drive to stop drugs
in our country.''
   Everett Ellis Briggs, U.S. ambassador to Honduras, on Sunday
denied a report in Sunday's New York Times that said that while he
was ambassador to Panama he had briefed Bush in 1985 on evidence of
drug trafficking by Noriega.
   ``I could not have briefed the vice president on Noriega's drug
running, drug smuggling or money laundering activities because we
simply did not have evidence of those activities at that time,''
Briggs said at a news conference in Tegucigalpa, Honduras.
   Neither Bush nor Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis had any
campaign appearances on Sunday.
   ``Can I compete with Dukakis and Bush?'' Jackson said. ``That's
Harvard and Yale. They have the prestige, they have the power
structure, they have the press, they have the pundits ... and yet I
must not surrender. I've always battled the odds and won. I'm a
survivor.''
   A number of his family members were in the audience, including
his wife Jacqueline and his two sons, Jesse Jr. and Jonathan, both
of whom were awarded degrees during the ceremony.
   Jackson reflected on his years at North Carolina A&T and on the
years since his graduation, recalling his activism as a participant
in civil rights sit-ins to demand desegregation of public
facilities in Greensboro.
   He urged the 900 graduating students in the Greensboro Coliseum
not to allow difficult circumstances to stifle their dreams.
   ``As I get closer to the White House, there are no more
impossible dreams,'' he said.
   Jackson said his showing has been strong despite being
out-funded by his Democratic rival.
   ``I've come from further back with fewer resources, running
strong and don't feel no ways tired,'' he said.
   ``Now just don't say `Run, Jesse Run.' I run that you might run.
If I run for president, surely you can run for governor. If I run
for president, surely you can run for senator.''
   Jackson, sounding a familiar theme, said many young blacks might
see him campaigning on television and suspect that he cannot
understand their difficulties.
   ``I was born in the slum, but the slum was not born in me,'' he
said, invoking his early years. Jackson's mother was an unmarried
teen-ager when she gave birth to him.
   ``Born in three-room house, parents who didn't have health
insurance. I understand. Bathroom on the back porch, slop jar by
the bed. I understand.
   ``Had to hang out clothes on nails. I understand. Wallpaper used
for windbreaker, not for decoration. I understand. Had stand by an
open stove to get heat. I really do understand.
   ``Against those odds ... I never earned the right to do less
than my best and you do not have the right than to do less than
your best,'' he told the students.
</TEXT>
