<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-88 2117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Sickman     05-08 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Sickman,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading American Expert On Chinese Art Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurence Sickman, former director of the
Nelson Art Gallery in Kansas City and an internationally renowned
expert in Chinese art, has died at the age of 81.
   Sickman died Saturday at St. Luke's Hospital in Kansas City
after a lengthy illness.
   ``He was the dean of Chinese art in the Western world, and was
so recognized,'' said Marc F. Wilson, the Nelson Gallery's current
director. ``He was a universally admired and respected man.''
   His long career as a connoisseur and historian of Oriental art
was instrumental in making the Nelson Gallery's Oriental collection
internationally known, said Herman Sutherland, one of the museum's
trustees.
   Sickman graduated from Harvard University in 1930 and began
working as an agent for art purchases in China in 1931, two years
before the museum opened. In 1935 he became the Nelson's first
curator of Oriental art. He retired in 1977, but remained active as
director emeritus until he developed lung cancer two years ago,
Wilson said.
   Sickman's only time away from the Nelson came during World War
II, when he served in the Army Air Corps combat intelligence group
in the Far East, and then as an adviser in the arts and monuments
section to Gen. Douglas MacArthur's headquarters in Tokyo. He was
awarded the Legion of Merit in 1946.
</TEXT>
