<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos Memorial,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Memorial Service For Marcos' Mother</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 supporters gathered at the
hillside estate of Ferdinand Marcos on Sunday for a three-hour
memorial service for the exiled Philippines president's mother.
   ``A Philippines that is free, democratic and strong, that is the
legacy of my mother,'' Marcos said in the eulogy.
   ``I shall not see her dead. I shall see her alive. She will be
with me every day of my life,'' said Marcos, who was denied
permission to return to the Philippines for the funeral of Josefa
Edralin-Marcos, who died there Wednesday.
   Philippines President Corazon Aquino, in a radio broadcast in
Manila on Sunday, reiterated that she decided against allowing
Marcos to return for security reasons.
   The Roman Catholic service here, which included recitation of
the burial rites, was held on the lawn of the Marcos home. A small
white tent was erected for the Marcos family and their close
friends.
   Marcos' wife, Imelda, and the couple's daughter, Irene, both
sang, and several leaders of Marcos support groups spoke.
   Following the service the supporters who were transported to the
estate on tour buses were fed McDonald's hamburgers, spaghetti and
traditional Filipino foods.
   Marcos and his family have lived here since fleeing Manila in
February 1986 during a largely non-violent uprising that brought
Mrs. Aquino to power.
</TEXT>
