<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Ecuador-Election 3rd-Writethru a0848 05-08 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador-Election, 3rd-Writethru, a0848,0755</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ecuador Picks Successor to Pro-U.S. President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Borja thanking voters.
Pickup 2nd graf pvs ``Borja's rival...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rodrigo Borja won Sunday's presidential
election in the runoff race between two leftists to succeed
pro-American President Leon Febres Cordero.
   ``Thank you, Ecuador, thank you,'' Borja said on television in
the capital. ``We will have a government by the people and for the
people.''
   Thousands of Borja's supporters in Quito, his highland
stronghold, swarmed into the streets to celebrate and caravans of
cars with their horns blaring packed the city's avenues.
   Borja's rival, Abdala Bucaram, conceded defeat in an address
over national television from his power base in Guayaquil.
   ``There are no excuses. Dr. Rodrigo Borja is the president of
Ecuador,'' Bucaram said.
   With the count nearly complete, Borja had 1,584,483 of the valid
votes and Bucaram 1,344,200.
   Political analysts had said the election was too close to call.
Public opinion polls showed 25 percent of the country's 4.7 million
eligible voters still undecided in the final weeks of the campaign.
Election oficials had estimated the voter turnout would be about 80
percent.
   Borja and Bucaram had conducted a bitter campaign marked by
exchanges of insults in their race to replace Febres Cordero, a
conservative who has promoted free-market policies and befriended
the United States.
   Febres Cordero voted in Guayaquil and discounted persistent
rumors of a military coup if Bucaram is elected. Coups ``are out of
fashion,'' he said.
   Bucaram has charged that the right spread the rumors to try to
prevent him from winning.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The election pitted Borja, a 52-year-old law professor and
leader of the Democratic Left Party, against Bucaram, a
tough-talking 36-year-old populist who vowed to ``punish the
oligarchy.''
   Sirens and church bells echoed Sunday through the streets of
this city 9,300 feet high in the Andes, signaling opening of polls.
   Voters included colorfully dressed Highland Indians from the
outskirts of the capital. Indians make up 35 percent of Ecuador's
population of 10 million.
   Campaign violence intensified in the final weeks before the
election, leaving three people dead and more than a dozen wounded.
Newspapers and Roman Catholic Church leaders blamed the clashes on
the vitriolic rhetoric of the candidates.
   Bucaram, leader of the Roldosista Party, called his adversary a
drunkard, a drug addict and an atheist, a potentially damaging
accusation in this heavily Catholic nation. He also used coarse
street language to question Borja's manliness.
   Borja, an urbane, usually reserved politician from Quito,
responded with insults of his own, calling Bucaram a ``fascist
ignoramus.''
   Borja and Bucaram qualified for the runoff by leading a field of
10 candidates in the first round of voting Jan. 31. Borja won 20
percent of the vote, and Bucaram took 15.
   Febres Cordero, of the Social Christian Party, came in third, a
sign of his government's low popularity.
   Borja, who lost a close runoff to the president in 1984 and was
making his third bid for the presidency, pledged to reverse the
government's free-market economic policies and seek close ties to
the non-aligned movement.
   Bucaram is political boss of the huge slums that sprawl over the
outskirts of Guayaquil, the country's largest city and its major
port.
   His opponents accused him of making demagogic appeals to the
poor, including promises to give free shoes to all poor children
and nearly double the monthly minimum wage to $55.
   His followers affectionally call him ``the crazy one'' because
of his fiery speaking style. During the campaign, he recorded a
song titled ``That's Why They Call Me Crazy.''
   This small nation returned to democracy in 1979 after nine years
of civilian and military dictatorships.
   Febres Cordero, whose four-year term ends in August, has had a
stormy relationship with leftist and populist parties that
controlled Congress. He also put down a rebellion by an air force
commander halfway through his presidency.
   His successor faces the most serious national economic crisis
since Ecuador began exporting oil in the early 1970s.
   The economy shrank in 1987 by 3.5 percent, and inflation is
expected to climb to at least 50 percent this year, the highest
level since 1983.
   Febres Cordero's supporters blame the problems on a sharp drop
in the price of oil, Ecuador's main source of income, and economic
damage from a devastating earthquake in March 1987.
</TEXT>
