<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines-Earthquake     05-08 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Earthquake,0132</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Shakes Western Luzon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake shook western Luzon island
in the Philippines before dawn Monday, the Royal Observatory of
Hong Kong reported.
   The quake at 3:47 a.m. (3:47 p.m. EDT Sunday) was centered about
112 north-northwest of Manila and had an estimated magnitude of 5.4
on the Richter scale, the observatory reported.
   There were no immediate reports of damage or injuries.
   A quake of magnitude 5 can cause considerable damage in a
populated area while a quake measuring 6 on the Richter scale can
cause severe damage.
   The Richter scale gauges energy released by an earthquake as
measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. Every
increase of one number means ground motion is 10 times greater.
</TEXT>
