<HEAD>Thunderstorms Over Central States With Hail</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with tornadoes, injuries in
Illinois, downgrade Indiana tornado to high wind. Picks up 7th graf
pvs ``Late Saturday...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms moved across parts of the Mississippi
Valley and the Plains and Midwest on Sunday, spawning tornadoes in
Iowa and Illinois and dropping hailstones up to 2{ inches in
diameter.
   Tornado watches covering the afternoon and early evening were
issued for parts of Iowa, Missouri, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Illinois,
Oklahoma and Arkansas.
   Some injuries were reported as a tornado touched down at Elwood,
Ill., just south of Joliet, Sunday night, tearing the roof off a
condominium and strewing debris, the National Weather Service said.
Several other tornadoes touched down in Illinois, and aircraft were
overturned at the Rockford, Ill., airport as winds gusted to 81 mph.
   Showers and thunderstorms were accompanied by heavy rain and
hail from southwestern Wisconsin and southeastern Minnesota through
central and southwestern Iowa, western Missouri and eastern Kansas
into eastern Oklahoma and Arkansas.
   More than two dozen tornadoes swept through southeast Iowa,
damaging several homes near Ottumwa and tipping over mobile homes
in Libertyville. High winds also blew tree limbs through power
lines, causing scattered power outages around Des Moines. No
serious injuries were reported.
   High winds in Talbot, Ind., about five miles east of the
Illinois border, moved and damaged a storage shed, authorities.
Several unconfirmed tornadoes were reported in southern and central
Wisconsin, where storms damaged roofs and knocked down trees and
power lines. No injuries were reported in either state.
   Late Saturday, a tornado struck a mobile home southwest of
Omaha, Neb., and killed two people.
   Hail up to 2{ inches in diameter fell just west of Lawrence,
Kan., during the morning.
   Hail as big as golfballs pelted the Iowa towns of Anamosa and
Afton, and the areas of Carlise and Indianola, southeast of Des
Moines, and parts of Kansas and Missouri.
   Wind gusts of 50 mph were clocked while the storms crossed
central Iowa and tree limbs were reported blown down at
Marshalltown. Waterloo had gusts to 58 mph and three-quarter-inch
hail, and Dubuque recorded gusts of 67 mph.
   Hail up to an inch and a half in diameter fell in Missouri's
Nodaway County, about 50 miles north of Kansas City.
   To the south, showers and thunderstorms moved into northern
Louisiana and southern Arkansas, with one-inch hail reported at
Canton, Ark. Lightning set a house afire at Lone Star, Texas, the
weather service said.
   Showers were scattered ahead of the main area of thunderstorms,
extending from southern Illinois through western Kentucky and
western Tennessee into northern Alabama. Behind the front, showers
were scattered from central South Dakota into the Nebraska
Panahndle.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered from southwestern Oregon into
the northern valleys of California.
   Muskegon, Mich., warmed to a record 83 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 35
degrees at Rock Springs, Wyo., to 97 at Laredo, Texas. The low for
the day was 22 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the Great Lakes region through the Ohio and Tennessee valleys
into the lower Mississippi Valley and central Gulf Coast.
   Highs in the 50s were predicted in southwestern Wyoming; in the
80s from the desert Southwest to the southern Plains, the lower
Mississippi and Tennessee valleys and the Southeast into Florida;
in the 90s over the Arizona deserts, and south-central Texas and
the Rio Grande Valley; and in the 60s or 70s across much of the
rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
