<FILEID>AP-NR-05-08-88 2310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Commencements     05-08 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commencements,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cartoonist, Ex-Justice, Geographer And Actress Address Grads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Doonesbury'' cartoonist Garry Trudeau
received an honorary degree from Duke University and drew some
comfort from President Reagan's reading habits.
   ``If you read every (comic) strip published in The Washington
Post, as Larry Speakes now claims the president does, it takes
roughly eight minutes a day, which means by my tally the leader of
the free world has spent a total of 14 days, 16 hours and 48
minutes of his presidency reading comics,'' Trudeau told about
2,400 graduates and 19,000 others at a commencement ceremony.
   ``Which explains a lot. Of course that information is downright
reassuring when compared with the news that he has spent a
comparable amount of time reading his horoscope.''
   In Chapel Hill, U.S. Sen. Dale Bumpers told more than 5,000
graduates at the University of North Carolina that his generation
had left them a dangerous legacy of debt.
   ``The threat is ominous. With a $2.4 trillion dollar debt. But
we are handing you a free republic _ a democracy and it's up to you
to keep it,'' Bumpers said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RADFORD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Supreme Court Justice Arthur J.
Goldberg said free compulsory public education should be extended
to include two years of college.
   ``In this high-tech era, we require a higher level of free
public education than now provided,'' Goldberg told Radford
University's 967 graduates at commencement exercises Saturday.
``Otherwise, our leadership in the free world, both industrially
and militarily, is at risk.''
   Goldberg, an associate justice on the Supreme Court from 1962 to
1965, also suggested students be given amnesty for outstanding
loans and that parents of graduates be given tax breaks.
   ``No graduate of a university should be burdened with a
substantial debt in embarking a career and raising a family,'' said
Goldberg, a visiting professor at the university this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans need to learn more about the world
and its array of cultures if the United States is to prosper in the
global marketplace, the president of the National Geographic
Society said Sunday.
   ``We face a critical economic need to understand foreign
consumers, markets, customs, foreign strengths and weaknesses,''
Gilbert M. Grosvenor told graduates of Miami University's School of
Business Administration and the School of Education and Allied
Professions.
   ``Americans can no longer negotiate in English to sell our
products or be oblivious to cultural differences.''
